{"title_page": "M\u00edchel Salgado", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Spanish name|Salgado|Fern\u00e1ndez}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = M\u00edchel Salgado\n|image = M\u00edchel Salgado 2018.jpg\n|image_size = 200px\n|caption = Salgado playing in a legends match in 2018\n|fullname = Miguel \u00c1ngel Salgado Fern\u00e1ndez<ref name=RM>{{cite web|url=https://www.realmadrid.com/sobre-el-real-madrid/el-club/historia/jugadores-de-leyenda-futbol/michel-salgado|title=El triunfo del esfuerzo|trans-title=The triumph of effort|publisher=Real Madrid CF|language=Spanish|accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1975|10|22|df=y}}<ref name=Profile>{{cite news|url=https://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/envivos/fichas/1/058/314.html|title=M\u00cdCHEL SALGADO Fern\u00e1ndez|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_place = [[As Neves]], Spain<ref name=Profile/>\n|height = {{height|m=1.74}}<ref name=Profile/>\n|position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Right back]]\n|currentclub = [[Galicia national football team|Galicia]] (manager)\n|youthyears1 = 1990\u20131992 | youthclubs1 = Cristo Victoria\n|youthyears2 = 1992\u20131994 | youthclubs2 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]]\n|years1 = 1994\u20131995 | clubs1 = [[Celta de Vigo B|Celta B]] | caps1 = 20 | goals1 = 0\n|years2 = 1995\u20131999 | clubs2 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]] | caps2 = 92 | goals2 = 3\n|years3 = 1996\u20131997 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[UD Salamanca|Salamanca]] (loan) | caps3 = 36  | goals3 = 1\n|years4 = 1999\u20132009 | clubs4 = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] | caps4 = 254 | goals4 = 4\n|years5 = 2009\u20132012 | clubs5 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] | caps5 = 66 | goals5 = 0\n|years6 = 2018 | clubs6 = [[Independiente F.C.|Independiente]] | caps6 = 1 | goals6 = 0\n|totalcaps = 469 | totalgoals = 8\n|nationalyears1 = 1994 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]] | nationalcaps1 = 7 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n|nationalyears2 = 1995 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain U19]] | nationalcaps2 = 2 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n|nationalyears3 = 1995 | nationalteam3 = [[Spain national under-20 football team|Spain U20]] | nationalcaps3 = 5 | nationalgoals3 = 1\n|nationalyears4 = 1996\u20131998 | nationalteam4 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps4 = 10 | nationalgoals4 = 0\n|nationalyears5 = 1998\u20132006 | nationalteam5 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps5 = 53 | nationalgoals5 = 0\n|nationalyears6 = 2005 | nationalteam6 = [[Galicia national football team|Galicia]] | nationalcaps6 = 1 | nationalgoals6 = 0\n|manageryears1 = 2016\u2013 | managerclubs1 = [[Galicia national football team|Galicia]]\n}}\n'''Miguel \u00c1ngel \"M\u00edchel\" Salgado Fern\u00e1ndez''' (born 22 October 1975) is a Spanish retired professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right back]].\n\nNicknamed ''Il Due''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/papel/2005/01/22/deportes/1747116.html|title=Diez a\u00f1os de ''Il Due''|trans-title=Ten years of ''Il Due''|newspaper=El Mundo|language=Spanish|date=22 January 2005|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref> (two in Italian), he was known for his combative tackling and attacking play. Attesting to his aggressive style, his former [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] teammate [[Steve McManaman]] \u2013 where he spent an entire decade, after excellent displays at [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]] \u2013 once described him as \"the hardest person in the world....a genuine psychopath, even in training.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/clubs/premier-league/blackburn-rovers/10-things-you-didn-t-know-about-Miguel-Salgado-article109539.html|title=10 things you didn't know about Miguel Salgado|newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]]|last=Aikman|first=Richard|date=11 August 2009|accessdate=25 August 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120005042/http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/clubs/premier-league/blackburn-rovers/10-things-you-didn-t-know-about-Miguel-Salgado-article109539.html|archivedate=20 January 2012}}</ref> He also played three seasons in England, with [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]].\n\nSalgado, who appeared in 341 [[La Liga]] matches and scored seven goals, represented the [[Spain national football team|Spanish national team]] over eight years, collecting more than 50 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] and appearing in one [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] and one [[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Celta===\nBorn in [[As Neves]], [[Province of Pontevedra|Pontevedra]], [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], Salgado began his professional career with hometown's [[RC Celta de Vigo]],<ref name=CELTA>{{cite web|url=http://www.yojugueenelcelta.com/2008/04/michel-salgado.html|title=M\u00edchel Salgado|publisher=Yo Jugu\u00e9 en el Celta|language=Spanish|date=3 April 2008|accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> making his [[La Liga]] debut on 22 January 1995 in a 0\u20134 away loss against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/gradario/hemeroteca/2017/01/22/cumplen-22-anos-debut-michel-salgado-celta/00031485082257032771510.htm|title=Se cumplen 22 a\u00f1os del debut de M\u00edchel Salgado con el Celta|trans-title=22 years of M\u00edchel Salgado's debut with Celta|newspaper=[[La Voz de Galicia]]|language=Spanish|date=22 January 2017|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> He was loaned for a season to [[UD Salamanca]] in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]], and after his return became the first-choice in his position.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/2016/08/23/celta-de-vigo/685832-suena-michel-michel-salgado.html|title=Suena M\u00edchel, M\u00edchel Salgado|trans-title=The man of the hour is M\u00edchel, M\u00edchel Salgado|publisher=[[Vavel]]|last=Laborda Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Adri\u00e0|language=Spanish|date=23 August 2016|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nWhilst at Celta, Salgado was involved in an incident with [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]'s [[Juninho Paulista]] in February 1998: after a dangerous challenge, the Brazilian was sidelined for six months and missed [[1998 FIFA World Cup|that year]]'s [[FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=EURO>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/spain/squad/743428.stm|title=Miguel Salgado|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/1998/febrero/02/deportes/juninho.html|title=Juninho, roto|trans-title=Juninho, torn|newspaper=El Mundo|last1=\u00c1lvarez|first1=R. J.|last2=Izquierdo|first2=C. G.|language=Spanish|date=2 February 1998|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/1998/02/19/deportes/19N0083.html|title=El Celta exige para M\u00edchel Salgado el beneficio de la duda|trans-title=Celta demand benefit of doubt for M\u00edchel Salgado|newspaper=El Mundo|language=Spanish|date=19 February 1998|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nSalgado scored a career-best three goals in the [[1998\u201399 La Liga|1998\u201399 campaign]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1998/09/27/deportes/906847203_850215.html|title=El Celta empata en el descuento|trans-title=Celta draw in injury time|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|last=Besa|first=Ram\u00f3n|language=Spanish|date=27 September 1998|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1998/12/14/deportes/913590010_850215.html|title=El Celta expone su orgullo|trans-title=Celta showcase pride|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|last=Campos|first=Pablo|language=Spanish|date=14 December 1998|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.abc.es/nav/Navigate.exe/hemeroteca/madrid/abc/1999/02/08/070.html|title=No lo tuvo tan f\u00e1cil el Celta|trans-title=Celta did not have it so easy|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=Spanish|date=8 February 1999|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> helping his team finish fifth and [[1999\u20132000 UEFA Cup|qualify]] for the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]].<ref name=EURO/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/span99.html|title=Spain 1998/99|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|last=Adrados|first=Juan Pedro|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=CELTA/>\n\n===Real Madrid===\nIn 1999, Salgado was purchased by Real Madrid for [[Euro|\u20ac]]11,000,000,<ref name=EURO/> playing 29 league games in [[1999\u20132000 La Liga|his first season]] while also helping the club [[1999\u201300 UEFA Champions League|win]] the [[UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/may/24/championsleague.sport1|title=Real Madrid 3\u20130 Valencia|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=24 May 2000|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref> He was the [[Madrid|capital]] side's starter during his first seven years, but was relegated to [[Substitute (association football)|the bench]] by former [[Sevilla FC]] youngster [[Sergio Ramos]] in [[2006\u201307 La Liga|2006\u201307]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtve.es/deportes/20090824/sentido-homenaje-salgado-bernabeu/289928.shtml|title=Sentido homenaje a Salgado en el Bernab\u00e9u|trans-title=Hearfelt homage to Salgado at the Bernab\u00e9u|publisher=[[RTVE]]|language=Spanish|date=24 August 2009|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Despedida de M\u00edchel Salgado.JPG|thumb|left|Real Madrid fans show their appreciation of Salgado's ten years service to the club.]]\nSalgado was still able to contribute with 16 matches for the ''Merengues''' 30th national title, mainly due to injuries to [[Pepe (footballer, born 1983)|Pepe]], with Ramos being relocated to [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre back]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2007/08/04/mas_futbol/1186178407_850215.html|title=Michel Salgado: \"Quiero seguir en el Real Madrid\"|trans-title=Michel Salgado: \"I want to continue in Real Madrid\"|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|language=Spanish|date=4 August 2007|accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref> In the following two campaigns he featured very rarely (only 17 appearances combined), being [[Ejection (sports)|sent off]] in the final game of [[2008-09 La Liga|2008\u201309]], a 1\u20132 loss at [[CA Osasuna]] on 31 May 2009 as Madrid slumped to a fifth consecutive league defeat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defensacentral.com/real_madrid/29711-casillas-y-teixeira-salvan-a-osasuna-osasuna-2-1-real-madrid/|title=Casillas y Teixeira salvan a Osasuna|trans-title=Casillas and Teixeira save Osasuna|publisher=Defensa Central|last=Torrico|first=Eduardo|language=Spanish|date=31 May 2009|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nSalgado was released in early August 2009, with the team already midway into pre-season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1202777494192/noticia/ComunicadoOficial/MICHEL_SALGADO_2009-08-04.htm|title=Official announcement|publisher=Real Madrid CF|date=4 August 2009|accessdate=4 August 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807024936/http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1202777494192/noticia/ComunicadoOficial/MICHEL_SALGADO_2009-08-04.htm|archivedate=7 August 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Blackburn Rovers===\nAged nearly 34, Salgado moved to [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] of the [[Premier League]] on 19 August 2009, signing a two-year deal after impressing manager [[Sam Allardyce]] whilst on trial. He went on to say he was happy to be playing for his new club, intending to retire at [[Ewood Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackburncitizen.co.uk/sport/4553432.Salgado_set_for_Blackburn_Rovers_move/|title=Salgado set for Blackburn Rovers|publisher=Blackburn Citizen|date=19 August 2009|accessdate=19 August 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/blackburn-rovers/6055073/Blackburn-Rovers-complete-signing-of-former-Real-Madrid-full-back-Michel-Salgado.html|title=Blackburn Rovers complete signing of former Real Madrid full-back Michel Salgado|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=19 August 2009|accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:M\u00edchel Salgado in Tehran.jpg|175px|thumb|Salgado in a charity match in [[Tehran]] in 2015]]\nSalgado made his competitive debut on 12 September 2009, against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] as a late substitute (3\u20131 home win).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/8247147.stm|title=Blackburn 3\u20131 Wolverhampton|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Roopanarine|first=Les|date=12 September 2009|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> On 27 October he scored his first goal for his new team, in a [[2009\u201310 Football League Cup|5\u20132 victory]] over [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] in the [[EFL Cup|Football League Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/league_cup/8323055.stm|title=Blackburn 5\u20132 Peterborough|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 October 2009|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 January 2011, 35-year-old Salgado agreed to a contract extension.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballpress.net/?action=read&idsel=77946|title=Salgado happy to extend his Blackburn deal|publisher=Football Press|date=28 January 2011|accessdate=16 June 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130012718/http://www.footballpress.net/?action=read&idsel=77946|archive-date=30 January 2011}}</ref> He was first-choice for the first games in the [[2011\u201312 Premier League|2011\u201312 season]], until picking up an injury.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2051889/BLACKBURN-v-Tottenham-Hamstrung-Michel-Salgado-replaced-Jason-Lowe.html|title=Blackburn v Tottenham: Hamstrung Salgado to be replaced by Lowe|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=21 October 2011|accessdate=15 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/grella-nelsen-still-sidelined-blackburn-rovers-1997361|title=Grella, Nelsen still sidelined for Blackburn Rovers|publisher=Tribal Football|last=Slevison|first=Andrew|date=21 October 2011|accessdate=15 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nBlackburn manager [[Steve Kean]] revealed in December 2011 that Salgado was being omitted from the squad as his contract stated that the player was entitled to a new deal if he played nine more matches in the campaign, the club not being able to afford fresh terms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/7387948/|title=Salgado 'frozen out'|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=20 December 2011|accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/127135.html|title=Blackburn can't afford to play me \u2013 Salgado|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=20 December 2011|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Futsal / Later years===\nAged 40, Salgado came out of retirement to join [[Kochi 5s]] in India's [[Premier Futsal]] as a [[marquee player]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/136/india/2016/07/12/25561652/premier-futsal-squads-announced-for-inaugural-edition|title=Premier Futsal: Squads announced for inaugural edition|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=12 July 2016|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> He later was part of the board of Heritage Sports Holdings, which owned the football clubs [[Gibraltar United F.C.]] and [[UD Los Barrios]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/futbol/mas-futbol/tercera-division/2017/12/13/5a3165fcca47413e208b4689.html|title=Michel Salgado, al rescate de la UD Los Barrios de Tercera|trans-title=Michel Salgado, to the rescue of UD Los Barrios from ''Tercera''|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|last=Pi\u00f1ero|first=Margota|language=Spanish|date=13 December 2017|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hsh.football/who-we-are/|title=Who we are \u2013 Our story|publisher=Heritage Sports Holdings|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nSalgado came out of retirement again in April 2018, starting for [[Independiente F.C.]] in a 1\u20131 draw against [[C.D. Plaza Amador]] for the quarter-finals of the [[2017\u201318 Liga Paname\u00f1a de F\u00fatbol season|Panamanian Clausura tournament]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2018/04/29/internacional/1524970634_622765.html|title=M\u00edchel Salgado reaparece en Panam\u00e1 con un empate|trans-title=M\u00edchel Salgado reappears in Panama with a draw|newspaper=Diario AS|language=Spanish|date=29 April 2018|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nSalgado won the first of his 53 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] on 5 September 1998, in an infamous 2\u20133 loss in [[Cyprus national football team|Cyprus]] for the [[UEFA Euro 2000]] [[UEFA Euro 2000 qualifying|qualifiers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/1998/septiembre/05/deportes/futbol.html|title=Espa\u00f1a cae ante Chipre, un equipo repleto de aficionados|trans-title=Spain fall against Cyprus, team filled with amateurs|newspaper=El Mundo|language=Spanish|date=5 September 1998|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref> He was part of the nation's squads at Euro 2000 and the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], starting in the former and being backup in the latter to Real Madrid teammate Ramos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/es/espa%C3%B1a-arabia-saud%C3%AD-salgado-contra-los-hijos-del-desierto/a-2064778|title=Espa\u00f1a \u2013 Arabia Saud\u00ed: Salgado contra los \"hijos del desierto\"|trans-title=Spain \u2013 Saudi Arabia: Salgado against the \"desert sons\"|publisher=[[DW-TV]]|language=Spanish|date=23 June 2006|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nDue to last-minute injuries, Salgado missed out on the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=188686.html|title=Goodbye pharoes, hello Faro|publisher=UEFA|date=12 June 2004|accessdate=1 October 2012}}</ref> He also represented the [[Galicia national football team|Galician autonomous team]], which he later coached alongside [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]]'s [[Fran (Spanish footballer)|Fran]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.atlantico.net/articulo/deportes/riazor-escenario-galicia-venezuela-fran-y-michel-salgado-tecnicos/20160414114706525419.html|title=Riazor, escenario del Galicia-Venezuela con Fran y M\u00edchel Salgado de t\u00e9cnicos|trans-title=Riazor, venue of Galicia-Venezuela with Fran and M\u00edchel Salgado as managers|newspaper=[[Atl\u00e1ntico Diario]]|language=Spanish|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cadenaser.com/emisora/2016/05/06/radio_vigo/1462540258_564344.html|title=El Celta protagonista de la selecci\u00f3n gallega|trans-title=Celta protagonist of Galician national team|publisher=[[Cadena SER]]|last=Montes|first=Paula|language=Spanish|date=6 May 2016|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 September 2018, Salgado was named assistant manager to the [[Egypt national football team|Egyptian national team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/michel-salgado-resumes-duty-as-egypt-assistant-coach/oejfo1i6xkwv1v7fm65u064c8|title=Michel Salgado resumes duty as Egypt assistant coach|publisher=Goal|last=Oludare|first=Shina|date=4 September 2018|accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSalgado is married to Malula Sanz, daughter of former Real Madrid president [[Lorenzo Sanz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hola.com/famosos/2009/04/15/michel-salgado/|title=M\u00edchel Salgado and Malula Sanz esperan su tercer hijo|trans-title=M\u00edchel Salgado and Malula Sanz expect their third child|publisher=[[\u00a1Hola!]]|language=Spanish|date=15 April 2009|accessdate=4 November 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090830191312/http://www.hola.com/famosos/2009/04/15/michel-salgado/|archive-date=30 August 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/j/j2014.html|title=Salgado: Miguel \u00c1ngel Salgado Fern\u00e1ndez|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=26 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=Soccerway>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/miguel-angel-salgado-fernandez/323/|title=M\u00edchel Salgado|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colspan=2 | League Cup\n! colspan=2 | Continental\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n! Season\n! Club\n! League\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n! Apps !! Goals\n|-\n! colspan=3 |Spain\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[Copa del Rey]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Copa de la Liga]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[1994\u201395 La Liga|1994\u221295]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[La Liga]]||14||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||15||0\n|-\n|[[1995\u201396 La Liga|1995\u221296]]||18||0||5||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||23||0\n|-\n|[[1996\u201397 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|1996\u201397]]||[[UD Salamanca|Salamanca]]||[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]]||36||1||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||38||1\n|-\n|[[1997\u201398 La Liga|1997\u221298]]||rowspan=\"2\"|[[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]]||rowspan=\"2\"|La Liga||25||0||5||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||0||0||30||0\n|-\n|[[1998\u201399 La Liga|1998\u221299]]||35||3||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||7||0||44||3\n|-\n|[[1999\u20132000 La Liga|1999\u221200]]||rowspan=\"10\"|[[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]]||rowspan=\"10\"|La Liga||29||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||17||0||46||0\n|-\n|[[2000\u201301 La Liga|2000\u221201]]||27||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||11||0||38||1\n|-\n|[[2001\u201302 La Liga|2001\u221202]]||35||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||14||0||50||0\n|-\n|[[2002\u201303 La Liga|2002\u221203]]||35||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||16||1||51||1\n|-\n|[[2003\u201304 La Liga|2003\u221204]]||35||1||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||10||0||46||1\n|-\n|[[2004\u201305 La Liga|2004\u221205]]||28||2||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||9||0||37||2\n|-\n|[[2005\u201306 La Liga|2005\u221206]]||27||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||5||0||33||0\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 La Liga|2006\u221207]]||16||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0||17||0\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 La Liga|2007\u221208]]||8||0||3||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||2||0||13||0\n|-\n|[[2008\u201309 La Liga|2008\u221209]]||9||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||1||0||10||0\n|-\n! colspan=3 |England\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | [[FA Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n! colspan=2 | [[UEFA|Europe]]\n! colspan=2 | Total\n|-\n|[[2009\u201310 Premier League|2009\u201310]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn]]||rowspan=\"3\"|[[Premier League]]||21||0||1||0||4||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||26||1\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 Premier League|2010\u201311]]||36||0||2||0||0||0||0||0||38||0\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 Premier League|2011\u201312]]||9||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||9||0\n|-\n!rowspan=2| Country !!colspan=2| Spain\n!377||8||21||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||86||1||470||9\n|-\n!colspan=2|England\n!66||0||3||0||4||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||73||1\n|-\n!colspan=3|Total\n!443||8||24||0||4||1||86||1||543||10\n|}\n\n===International===\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=18345|title=M\u00edchel Salgado|publisher=European Football|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! colspan=3 | [[Spain national football team|Spain]]\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|-\n|1998||3||0\n|-\n|1999||9||0\n|-\n|2000||5||0\n|-\n|2001||0||0\n|-\n|2002||5||0\n|-\n|2003||10||0\n|-\n|2004||8||0\n|-\n|2005||8||0\n|-\n|2006||5||0\n|-\n!Total||53||0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Club===\n'''Real Madrid'''<ref name=RM/><ref name=Soccerway/>\n*[[La Liga]]: [[2000\u201301 La Liga|2000\u201301]], [[2002\u201303 La Liga|2002\u201303]], [[2006\u201307 La Liga|2006\u201307]], [[2007\u201308 La Liga|2007\u201308]]\n*[[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]: [[2001 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|2001]], [[2003 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|2003]], [[2008 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|2008]]\n*[[UEFA Champions League]]: [[1999\u20132000 UEFA Champions League|1999\u20132000]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1999/matches/round=1290/match=64833/postmatch/lineups/index.html|title=Real Madrid 3\u20130 Valencia|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> [[2001\u201302 UEFA Champions League|2001\u201302]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2001/matches/round=1549/match=1025482/index.html|title=Leverkusen 1\u20132 Real Madrid|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]]: [[2002 Intercontinental Cup|2002]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512302.html|title=Toyota Cup 2002|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=20 August 2014|url-status=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071201032333/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512302.html|archivedate=1 December 2007}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[2002 UEFA Super Cup|2002]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/supercup/history/season=2002/round=1622/match=69590/report=lu.html|title=Real Madrid 3\u20131 Feyenoord|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=20 August 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130105200905/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/supercup/history/season=2002/round=1622/match=69590/report=lu.html|archive-date=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===International===\n'''Spain U21'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]: [[1998 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|1998]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/history/season=1998/index.html|title=1998: Iv\u00e1n P\u00e9rez applies finishing touch|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=EURO/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{BDFutbol|2014}}\n* {{soccerbase|id=19974}}\n* {{NFT player|pid=6236}}\n* {{FIFA player|176639}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Spain squads\n|bg = #db000d\n|fg = #fbea0e\n|list1 =\n{{Spain squad UEFA Euro 2000}}\n{{Spain squad 2006 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Galicia national football team managers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salgado, Michel}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from O Condado]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Galician footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Celta de Vigo B players]]\n[[Category:RC Celta de Vigo players]]\n[[Category:UD Salamanca players]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid CF players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Blackburn Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n[[Category:Spain youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2000 players]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Panama]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in India]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:Sanz family]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Spanish name|Salgado|Fern\u00e1ndez}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n|name = M\u00edchel Salgado\n|image = M\u00edchel Salgado 2018.jpg\n|image_size = 200px\n|caption = Salgado playing in a legends match in 2018\n|fullname = Miguel \u00c1ngel Salgado Fern\u00e1ndez<ref name=RM>{{cite web|url=https://www.realmadrid.com/sobre-el-real-madrid/el-club/historia/jugadores-de-leyenda-futbol/michel-salgado|title=El triunfo del esfuerzo|trans-title=The triumph of effort|publisher=Real Madrid CF|language=Spanish|accessdate=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1975|10|22|df=y}}<ref name=Profile>{{cite news|url=https://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/envivos/fichas/1/058/314.html|title=M\u00cdCHEL SALGADO Fern\u00e1ndez|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=Spanish|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_place = [[As Neves]], Spain<ref name=Profile/>\n|height = {{height|m=1.74}}<ref name=Profile/>\n|position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Right back]]\n|currentclub = [[Galicia national football team|Galicia]] (manager)\n|youthyears1 = 1990\u20131992 | youthclubs1 = Cristo Victoria\n|youthyears2 = 1992\u20131994 | youthclubs2 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]]\n|years1 = 1994\u20131995 | clubs1 = [[Celta de Vigo B|Celta B]] | caps1 = 20 | goals1 = 0\n|years2 = 1995\u20131999 | clubs2 = [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]] | caps2 = 92 | goals2 = 3\n|years3 = 1996\u20131997 | clubs3 = \u2192 [[UD Salamanca|Salamanca]] (loan) | caps3 = 36  | goals3 = 1\n|years4 = 1999\u20132009 | clubs4 = [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] | caps4 = 254 | goals4 = 4\n|years5 = 2009\u20132012 | clubs5 = [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] | caps5 = 66 | goals5 = 0\n|years6 = 2018 | clubs6 = [[Independiente F.C.|Independiente]] | caps6 = 1 | goals6 = 0\n|totalcaps = 469 | totalgoals = 8\n|nationalyears1 = 1994 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national under-18 football team|Spain U18]] | nationalcaps1 = 7 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n|nationalyears2 = 1995 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain U19]] | nationalcaps2 = 2 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n|nationalyears3 = 1995 | nationalteam3 = [[Spain national under-20 football team|Spain U20]] | nationalcaps3 = 5 | nationalgoals3 = 1\n|nationalyears4 = 1996\u20131998 | nationalteam4 = [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain U21]] | nationalcaps4 = 10 | nationalgoals4 = 0\n|nationalyears5 = 1998\u20132006 | nationalteam5 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps5 = 53 | nationalgoals5 = 0\n|nationalyears6 = 2005 | nationalteam6 = [[Galicia national football team|Galicia]] | nationalcaps6 = 1 | nationalgoals6 = 0\n|manageryears1 = 2016\u2013 | managerclubs1 = [[Galicia national football team|Galicia]]\n}}\n'''Miguel \u00c1ngel \"M\u00edchel\" Salgado Fern\u00e1ndez''' (born 22 October 1975) is a Spanish retired professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right back]].\n\nNicknamed ''Il Due''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/papel/2005/01/22/deportes/1747116.html|title=Diez a\u00f1os de ''Il Due''|trans-title=Ten years of ''Il Due''|newspaper=El Mundo|language=Spanish|date=22 January 2005|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref> (two in Italian), he was known for his combative tackling and attacking play. Attesting to his aggressive style, his former [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]] teammate [[Steve McManaman]] \u2013 where he spent an entire decade, after excellent displays at [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]] \u2013 once described him as \"the hardest person in the world....a genuine psychopath, even in training.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/clubs/premier-league/blackburn-rovers/10-things-you-didn-t-know-about-Miguel-Salgado-article109539.html|title=10 things you didn't know about Miguel Salgado|newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]]|last=Aikman|first=Richard|date=11 August 2009|accessdate=25 August 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120005042/http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/clubs/premier-league/blackburn-rovers/10-things-you-didn-t-know-about-Miguel-Salgado-article109539.html|archivedate=20 January 2012}}</ref> He also played three seasons in England, with [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]].\n\nSalgado, who appeared in 341 [[La Liga]] matches and scored seven goals, represented the [[Spain national football team|Spanish national team]] over eight years, collecting more than 50 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] and appearing in one [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] and one [[UEFA European Championship|European Championship]].\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Celta===\nBorn in [[As Neves]], [[Province of Pontevedra|Pontevedra]], [[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]], Salgado began his professional career with hometown's [[RC Celta de Vigo]],<ref name=CELTA>{{cite web|url=http://www.yojugueenelcelta.com/2008/04/michel-salgado.html|title=M\u00edchel Salgado|publisher=Yo Jugu\u00e9 en el Celta|language=Spanish|date=3 April 2008|accessdate=12 June 2014}}</ref> making his [[La Liga]] debut on 22 January 1995 in a 0\u20134 away loss against [[Real Madrid CF|Real Madrid]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/gradario/hemeroteca/2017/01/22/cumplen-22-anos-debut-michel-salgado-celta/00031485082257032771510.htm|title=Se cumplen 22 a\u00f1os del debut de M\u00edchel Salgado con el Celta|trans-title=22 years of M\u00edchel Salgado's debut with Celta|newspaper=[[La Voz de Galicia]]|language=Spanish|date=22 January 2017|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> He was loaned for a season to [[UD Salamanca]] in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]], and after his return became the first-choice in his position.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vavel.com/es/futbol/2016/08/23/celta-de-vigo/685832-suena-michel-michel-salgado.html|title=Suena M\u00edchel, M\u00edchel Salgado|trans-title=The man of the hour is M\u00edchel, M\u00edchel Salgado|publisher=[[Vavel]]|last=Laborda Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Adri\u00e0|language=Spanish|date=23 August 2016|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nWhilst at Celta, Salgado was involved in an incident with [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]]'s [[Juninho Paulista]] in February 1998: after a dangerous challenge, the Brazilian was sidelined for six months and missed [[1998 FIFA World Cup|that year]]'s [[FIFA World Cup]].<ref name=EURO>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/teams/spain/squad/743428.stm|title=Miguel Salgado|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=6 October 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/1998/febrero/02/deportes/juninho.html|title=Juninho, roto|trans-title=Juninho, torn|newspaper=El Mundo|last1=\u00c1lvarez|first1=R. J.|last2=Izquierdo|first2=C. G.|language=Spanish|date=2 February 1998|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/1998/02/19/deportes/19N0083.html|title=El Celta exige para M\u00edchel Salgado el beneficio de la duda|trans-title=Celta demand benefit of doubt for M\u00edchel Salgado|newspaper=El Mundo|language=Spanish|date=19 February 1998|accessdate=4 April 2009}}</ref>\n\nSalgado scored a career-best three goals in the [[1998\u201399 La Liga|1998\u201399 campaign]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1998/09/27/deportes/906847203_850215.html|title=El Celta empata en el descuento|trans-title=Celta draw in injury time|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|last=Besa|first=Ram\u00f3n|language=Spanish|date=27 September 1998|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1998/12/14/deportes/913590010_850215.html|title=El Celta expone su orgullo|trans-title=Celta showcase pride|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|last=Campos|first=Pablo|language=Spanish|date=14 December 1998|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.abc.es/nav/Navigate.exe/hemeroteca/madrid/abc/1999/02/08/070.html|title=No lo tuvo tan f\u00e1cil el Celta|trans-title=Celta did not have it so easy|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=Spanish|date=8 February 1999|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> helping his team finish fifth and [[1999\u20132000 UEFA Cup|qualify]] for the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]].<ref name=EURO/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tabless/span99.html|title=Spain 1998/99|publisher=[[RSSSF]]|last=Adrados|first=Juan Pedro|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=CELTA/>\n\n===Real Madrid===\nIn 1999, Salgado was purchased by Real Madrid for [[Euro|\u20ac]]11,000,000,<ref name=EURO/> playing 29 league games in [[1999\u20132000 La Liga|his first season]] while also helping the club [[1999\u201300 UEFA Champions League|win]] the [[UEFA Champions League]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/may/24/championsleague.sport1|title=Real Madrid 3\u20130 Valencia|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=24 May 2000|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref> He was the [[Madrid|capital]] side's starter during his first seven years, but was relegated to [[Substitute (association football)|the bench]] by former [[Sevilla FC]] youngster [[Sergio Ramos]] in [[2006\u201307 La Liga|2006\u201307]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtve.es/deportes/20090824/sentido-homenaje-salgado-bernabeu/289928.shtml|title=Sentido homenaje a Salgado en el Bernab\u00e9u|trans-title=Hearfelt homage to Salgado at the Bernab\u00e9u|publisher=[[RTVE]]|language=Spanish|date=24 August 2009|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Despedida de M\u00edchel Salgado.JPG|thumb|left|Real Madrid fans show their appreciation of Salgado's ten years service to the club.]]\nSalgado was still able to contribute with 16 matches for the ''Merengues''' 30th national title, mainly due to injuries to [[Pepe (footballer, born 1983)|Pepe]], with Ramos being relocated to [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre back]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2007/08/04/mas_futbol/1186178407_850215.html|title=Michel Salgado: \"Quiero seguir en el Real Madrid\"|trans-title=Michel Salgado: \"I want to continue in Real Madrid\"|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|language=Spanish|date=4 August 2007|accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref> In the following two campaigns he featured very rarely (only 17 appearances combined), being [[Ejection (sports)|sent off]] in the final game of [[2008-09 La Liga|2008\u201309]], a 1\u20132 loss at [[CA Osasuna]] on 31 May 2009 as Madrid slumped to a fifth consecutive league defeat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defensacentral.com/real_madrid/29711-casillas-y-teixeira-salvan-a-osasuna-osasuna-2-1-real-madrid/|title=Casillas y Teixeira salvan a Osasuna|trans-title=Casillas and Teixeira save Osasuna|publisher=Defensa Central|last=Torrico|first=Eduardo|language=Spanish|date=31 May 2009|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nSalgado was released in early August 2009, with the team already midway into pre-season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1202777494192/noticia/ComunicadoOficial/MICHEL_SALGADO_2009-08-04.htm|title=Official announcement|publisher=Real Madrid CF|date=4 August 2009|accessdate=4 August 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807024936/http://www.realmadrid.com/cs/Satellite/en/1202777494192/noticia/ComunicadoOficial/MICHEL_SALGADO_2009-08-04.htm|archivedate=7 August 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Blackburn Rovers===\nAged nearly 34, Salgado moved to [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] of the [[Premier League]] on 19 August 2009, signing a two-year deal after impressing manager [[Sam Allardyce]] whilst on trial. He went on to say he was happy to be playing for his new club, intending to retire at [[Ewood Park]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackburncitizen.co.uk/sport/4553432.Salgado_set_for_Blackburn_Rovers_move/|title=Salgado set for Blackburn Rovers|publisher=Blackburn Citizen|date=19 August 2009|accessdate=19 August 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/blackburn-rovers/6055073/Blackburn-Rovers-complete-signing-of-former-Real-Madrid-full-back-Michel-Salgado.html|title=Blackburn Rovers complete signing of former Real Madrid full-back Michel Salgado|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=19 August 2009|accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:M\u00edchel Salgado in Tehran.jpg|175px|thumb|Salgado in a charity match in [[Tehran]] in 2015]]\nSalgado made his competitive debut on 12 September 2009, against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] as a late substitute (3\u20131 home win).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/8247147.stm|title=Blackburn 3\u20131 Wolverhampton|publisher=BBC Sport|last=Roopanarine|first=Les|date=12 September 2009|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref> On 27 October he scored his first goal for his new team, in a [[2009\u201310 Football League Cup|5\u20132 triumph]] over [[Peterborough United F.C.|Peterborough United]] for the [[Football League Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/league_cup/8323055.stm|title=Blackburn 5\u20132 Peterborough|publisher=BBC Sport|date=27 October 2009|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 January 2011, 35-year-old Salgado agreed to a contract extension.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballpress.net/?action=read&idsel=77946|title=Salgado happy to extend his Blackburn deal|publisher=Football Press|date=28 January 2011|accessdate=16 June 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110130012718/http://www.footballpress.net/?action=read&idsel=77946|archive-date=30 January 2011}}</ref> He was first-choice for the first games in the [[2011\u201312 Premier League|2011\u201312 season]], until picking up an injury.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2051889/BLACKBURN-v-Tottenham-Hamstrung-Michel-Salgado-replaced-Jason-Lowe.html|title=Blackburn v Tottenham: Hamstrung Salgado to be replaced by Lowe|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|date=21 October 2011|accessdate=15 November 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/grella-nelsen-still-sidelined-blackburn-rovers-1997361|title=Grella, Nelsen still sidelined for Blackburn Rovers|publisher=Tribal Football|last=Slevison|first=Andrew|date=21 October 2011|accessdate=15 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nBlackburn manager [[Steve Kean]] revealed in December 2011 that Salgado was being omitted from the squad as his contract stated that the player was entitled to a new deal if he played nine more matches in the campaign, the club not being able to afford fresh terms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11095/7387948/|title=Salgado 'frozen out'|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=20 December 2011|accessdate=24 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/127135.html|title=Blackburn can't afford to play me \u2013 Salgado|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=20 December 2011|accessdate=3 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Futsal / Later years===\nAged 40, Salgado came out of retirement to join [[Kochi 5s]] in India's [[Premier Futsal]] as a [[marquee player]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/136/india/2016/07/12/25561652/premier-futsal-squads-announced-for-inaugural-edition|title=Premier Futsal: Squads announced for inaugural edition|publisher=[[Goal (website)|Goal]]|date=12 July 2016|accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> He later was part of the board of Heritage Sports Holdings, which owned the football clubs [[Gibraltar United F.C.]] and [[UD Los Barrios]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/futbol/mas-futbol/tercera-division/2017/12/13/5a3165fcca47413e208b4689.html|title=Michel Salgado, al rescate de la UD Los Barrios de Tercera|trans-title=Michel Salgado, to the rescue of UD Los Barrios from ''Tercera''|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|last=Pi\u00f1ero|first=Margota|language=Spanish|date=13 December 2017|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hsh.football/who-we-are/|title=Who we are \u2013 Our story|publisher=Heritage Sports Holdings|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nSalgado came out of retirement again in April 2018, starting for [[Independiente F.C.]] in a 1\u20131 draw against [[C.D. Plaza Amador]] for the quarter-finals of the [[2017\u201318 Liga Paname\u00f1a de F\u00fatbol season|Panamanian Clausura tournament]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2018/04/29/internacional/1524970634_622765.html|title=M\u00edchel Salgado reaparece en Panam\u00e1 con un empate|trans-title=M\u00edchel Salgado reappears in Panama with a draw|newspaper=Diario AS|language=Spanish|date=29 April 2018|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nSalgado won the first of his 53 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] on 5 September 1998, in an infamous 2\u20133 loss in [[Cyprus national football team|Cyprus]] for the [[UEFA Euro 2000]] [[UEFA Euro 2000 qualifying|qualifiers]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/1998/septiembre/05/deportes/futbol.html|title=Espa\u00f1a cae ante Chipre, un equipo repleto de aficionados|trans-title=Spain fall against Cyprus, team filled with amateurs|newspaper=El Mundo|language=Spanish|date=5 September 1998|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref> He was part of the nation's squads at Euro 2000 and the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], starting in the former and being backup in the latter to Real Madrid teammate Ramos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/es/espa%C3%B1a-arabia-saud%C3%AD-salgado-contra-los-hijos-del-desierto/a-2064778|title=Espa\u00f1a \u2013 Arabia Saud\u00ed: Salgado contra los \"hijos del desierto\"|trans-title=Spain \u2013 Saudi Arabia: Salgado against the \"desert sons\"|publisher=[[DW-TV]]|language=Spanish|date=23 June 2006|accessdate=15 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nDue to last-minute injuries, Salgado missed out on the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=188686.html|title=Goodbye pharoes, hello Faro|publisher=UEFA|date=12 June 2004|accessdate=1 October 2012}}</ref> He also represented the [[Galicia national football team|Galician autonomous team]], which he later coached alongside [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]]'s [[Fran (Spanish footballer)|Fran]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.atlantico.net/articulo/deportes/riazor-escenario-galicia-venezuela-fran-y-michel-salgado-tecnicos/20160414114706525419.html|title=Riazor, escenario del Galicia-Venezuela con Fran y M\u00edchel Salgado de t\u00e9cnicos|trans-title=Riazor, venue of Galicia-Venezuela with Fran and M\u00edchel Salgado as managers|newspaper=[[Atl\u00e1ntico Diario]]|language=Spanish|date=14 April 2016|accessdate=15 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cadenaser.com/emisora/2016/05/06/radio_vigo/1462540258_564344.html|title=El Celta protagonista de la selecci\u00f3n gallega|trans-title=Celta protagonist of Galician national team|publisher=[[Cadena SER]]|last=Montes|first=Paula|language=Spanish|date=6 May 2016|accessdate=30 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 September 2018, Salgado was named assistant manager to the [[Egypt national football team|Egyptian national team]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/michel-salgado-resumes-duty-as-egypt-assistant-coach/oejfo1i6xkwv1v7fm65u064c8|title=Michel Salgado resumes duty as Egypt assistant coach|publisher=Goal|last=Oludare|first=Shina|date=4 September 2018|accessdate=28 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSalgado is married to Malula Sanz, daughter of former Real Madrid president [[Lorenzo Sanz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hola.com/famosos/2009/04/15/michel-salgado/|title=M\u00edchel Salgado and Malula Sanz esperan su tercer hijo|trans-title=M\u00edchel Salgado and Malula Sanz expect their third child|publisher=[[\u00a1Hola!]]|language=Spanish|date=15 April 2009|accessdate=4 November 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090830191312/http://www.hola.com/famosos/2009/04/15/michel-salgado/|archive-date=30 August 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Club===\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/j/j2014.html|title=Salgado: Miguel \u00c1ngel Salgado Fern\u00e1ndez|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=26 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=Soccerway>{{cite web|url=https://int.soccerway.com/players/miguel-angel-salgado-fernandez/323/|title=M\u00edchel Salgado|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 | Club performance\n! colspan=2 | League\n! colspan=2 | Cup\n! colsp