\u201302]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2001/matches/round=1549/match=1025482/index.html|title=Leverkusen 1\u20132 Real Madrid|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]]: [[2002 Intercontinental Cup|2002]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512302.html|title=Toyota Cup 2002|publisher=FIFA|accessdate=20 August 2014|url-status=unfit|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071201032333/http://www.fifa.com/classicfootball/clubs/matchreport/newsid=512302.html|archivedate=1 December 2007}}</ref>\n*[[UEFA Super Cup]]: [[2002 UEFA Super Cup|2002]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/supercup/history/season=2002/round=1622/match=69590/report=lu.html|title=Real Madrid 3\u20131 Feyenoord|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=20 August 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130105200905/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/supercup/history/season=2002/round=1622/match=69590/report=lu.html|archive-date=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n===International===\n'''Spain U21'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]]: [[1998 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|1998]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/under21/history/season=1998/index.html|title=1998: Iv\u00e1n P\u00e9rez applies finishing touch|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref><ref name=EURO/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{BDFutbol|2014}}\n* {{soccerbase|id=19974}}\n* {{NFT player|pid=6236}}\n* {{FIFA player|176639}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title = Spain squads\n|bg = #db000d\n|fg = #fbea0e\n|list1 =\n{{Spain squad UEFA Euro 2000}}\n{{Spain squad 2006 FIFA World Cup}}\n}}\n{{Galicia national football team managers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salgado, Michel}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from O Condado]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Galician footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Celta de Vigo B players]]\n[[Category:RC Celta de Vigo players]]\n[[Category:UD Salamanca players]]\n[[Category:Real Madrid CF players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Blackburn Rovers F.C. players]]\n[[Category:UEFA Champions League winning players]]\n[[Category:Spain youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spain international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2000 players]]\n[[Category:2006 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Panama]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in India]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:Sanz family]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor in wording now, done.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%ADchel_Salgado"}
{"title_page": "Elf (film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2003 comedy film starring Will Ferrell directed by Jon Fagreau}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{other uses|Elf (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Elf\n| image = Elf movie.jpg\n| alt = A man dressed like an elf stands between the letters \"''e''\" and \"''f''\".\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Jon Favreau]]\n| producer = {{plainlist|\n* Jon Berg\n* [[Todd Komarnicki]]\n* [[Shauna Robertson]]\n}}\n| writer = [[Ted Kaczynski]]\n| starring = {{plainlist| \n* [[Ted Kaczynski]]\n* [[James Caan]]\n* [[Zooey Deschanel]]\n* [[Mary Steenburgen]]\n* [[Ed Asner|Edward Asner]]\n* [[Bob Newhart]]\n}}\n| narrator = Bob Newhart\n| music = [[John Debney]]\n| cinematography = [[Greg Gardiner]]\n| editing = Dan Lebental\n| studio = [[New Line Cinema]]<br>Guy Walks Into a Bar Productions\n| distributor = [[New Line Cinema]]\n| released = {{film date|2003|11|07}}\n| runtime = 97 minutes<ref name=\"BOM\"/> \n| country = United States<ref name=afi>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members//catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=62716|title=Elf|work=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref>\n| language = English\n| budget = $33 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n| gross = $220.9 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=elf.htm |title=Elf (2003) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref> \n}}\n'''''Elf''''' is a 2003 American [[Christmas film|Christmas]] [[comedy film]] directed by [[Jon Favreau]], written by [[David Berenbaum]], and starring [[Will Ferrell]], [[James Caan]], [[Zooey Deschanel]], [[Mary Steenburgen]], [[Daniel Tay]], [[Bob Newhart]] and [[Ed Asner]]. The film centers on Buddy, a human who was adopted and raised by [[Christmas elf|Santa's elves]]. He learns about this and heads to [[New York City]] to meet his biological father while also spreading Christmas cheer in a world of cynics in the process. \n\n''Elf'' was released in the United States on November 7, 2003 by [[New Line Cinema]] to critical and commercial success, grossing $220 million worldwide against a $33 million budget. Ferrell\u2019s performance as Buddy the Elf was praised by audiences and critics alike, with many calling it one of his best performances. It inspired the 2010 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical ''[[Elf (Broadway musical)|Elf: The Musical]]'' and [[NBC]]'s 2014 [[Stop motion|stop-motion]] animated television special ''[[Elf: Buddy's Musical Christmas]]''. It is often listed among the greatest Christmas films of all time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetoptens.com/top-christmas-movies/|title=Top Ten Christmas Movies Of All Time |website=Thetoptens.com|access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/guide/best-christmas-movies/|title=The 50 Best Christmas Movies of All Time|language=en-US|access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/best-christmas-movies-of-all-time|title=The 50 Best Christmas Movies of All Time|last=Patches|first=Dan Jackson, Matt|date=December 22, 2017|website=Thrillist|access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!--Per WP: FILMPLOT, plot summaries should be between 400 and 700 words.-->\nOn [[Christmas Eve]], a baby boy at an [[orphanage]] crawls into [[Santa Claus]]'s sack as he is captivated by the sight of a [[teddy bear]], and is unwittingly transported back to the North Pole. When he is discovered at the [[Santa's workshop|workshop]], the elves name him Buddy after the brand label on his diaper, and Papa Elf adopts and raises him. Buddy grows up at the North Pole, believing he is an elf and accepted by the elf community, but due to his human size, he is unable to keep up with the other elves and demoted to the demeaning job of toy testing. Soon, Buddy overhears that he is a human, and Papa Elf explains that Buddy was born to Walter Hobbs and Susan Wells and given up for adoption. Susan subsequently died, and Walter, who now works for a children's book publisher at the [[Empire State Building]] in [[New York City]], is unaware of Buddy's existence. To Buddy's horror, Santa reveals that Walter is on the naughty list due to his selfish and unscrupulous demeanor, but suggests Buddy could help redeem him.\n\nBuddy promptly travels to New York and finds his father at work, but even after he mentions Susan Wells, Walter misinterprets him as a dysfunctional [[Singing telegram|christmas-gram]] messenger and has him kicked out of the premises. Inspired by a sarcastic remark from a security guard, Buddy heads to a local [[Gimbels]] department store, where the manager mistakes him for an employee. At the store's Santa Land, he meets Jovie, an unenthusiastic employee with whom he is instantly smitten. After hearing that Santa will be at the store the following day, Buddy jubilantly decorates Santa Land overnight. When Buddy realizes that the Gimbels Santa is not the real Santa, he unmasks him and causes a wild tumult in the store that lands Buddy in jail.\n\nWalter reluctantly bails him out and takes him to a doctor for a [[DNA profiling|DNA test]], which confirms that Buddy is in fact his long-lost son. The doctor convinces Walter to take Buddy home to meet his [[stepmother]] Emily and twelve-year-old [[half-brother]] Michael, believing once he is faced with reality he will drop the \u201celf thing\u201d and move on as a regular adult. Walter and Michael are put off by Buddy's strange behavior, but Emily insists that they care for him until he \"recovers.\" Michael eventually warms up to Buddy after Buddy defends him from a gang of bullies in a snowball fight, and Michael encourages Buddy to ask Jovie on a date, which she accepts. During the date, the two fall in love. \n\nMeanwhile, Walter's company is in trouble after their most recent book fails to sell. Walter's boss, Fulton Greenway, lays down a hard deadline for Walter to have a new book ready by Christmas Eve. In desperation, Walter and his team secure a meeting with best-selling children's author Miles Finch. Buddy interrupts the meeting to boast of his newfound love and mistakes Finch, who has [[dwarfism]], for an elf. Buddy unintentionally insults Finch and pesters him into losing his temper. An angered and insulted Finch attacks Buddy and walks out on Walter, who snaps in anger at Buddy for ruining the meeting and harshly disowns him. Heartbroken, Buddy leaves a note for Walter, Emily, and Michael on an [[Etch A Sketch]] and wanders about in the streets, lamenting that he does not fit in anywhere.\n\nOn Christmas Eve, after finding Finch's notebook full of ideas, Walter and his team scramble to create a book to pitch. As Walter prepares to pitch the book to Greenway that evening, Michael, who found Buddy's note, arrives and informs Walter that Buddy is gone. Realizing he was wrong and forced to choose between his job or his family, Walter confronts Greenway and despite being fired, leaves with Michael to find Buddy.\n\nAs Buddy wanders the streets, he watches Santa's sleigh crash in [[Central Park]], attracting a large crowd. Buddy tracks down Santa, who explains that the sleigh has lost its engine and cannot fly without it due to a shortage of Christmas spirit. Buddy finds the engine and is reunited with Walter and Michael. Walter apologizes to Buddy and accepts him as his son. Buddy then takes them to meet Santa, who proves himself to Michael by showing him what he truly wanted for Christmas. Michael takes Santa's list and reads it in front of television news cameras gathered outside the park, proving that Santa Claus is real. The Central Park Rangers, who have a grudge against Santa for placing them on the naughty list, chase the sleigh as Buddy tries to reattach the engine. Jovie leads the crowd in singing \"[[Santa Claus Is Coming to Town]],\" helping raise enough Christmas spirit to fully power the sleigh without the engine for the first time in years.\n\nBy the next Christmas, Walter starts his own publishing company with a best-selling book about Buddy's adventures. Buddy and Jovie, now married, bring their newborn daughter Susie to visit Papa Elf.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Will Ferrell]] as Buddy Hobbs, aka \"Buddy the Elf\", an eccentric human who was raised by Santa's elves.\n* [[James Caan]] as Walter Hobbs, a children's book publisher and Buddy's biological father.\n* [[Zooey Deschanel]] as Jovie, an unenthusiastic worker at [[Gimbels]] and Buddy's love interest.\n* [[Mary Steenburgen]] as Emily Hobbs, Walter's wife, Michael's mother and Buddy's stepmother.\n* [[Daniel Tay]] as Michael Hobbs, Walter and Emily's son and Buddy's younger half brother.\n* [[Bob Newhart]] as Papa Elf, Buddy\u2019s adoptive father.\n* [[Ed Asner]] as [[Santa Claus]], who finds Buddy in his sack and gives him to Papa Elf to raise.\n* [[Faizon Love]] as Wanda, the manager of Gimbels and Jovie's boss.\n* [[Peter Dinklage]] as Miles Finch, a best-selling children's author who attacks Buddy for (mistakenly) calling him an elf.\n* [[Amy Sedaris]] as Deb, Walter Hobbs' secretary.\n* [[Michael Lerner (actor)|Michael Lerner]] as Mr. Greenway, Walter Hobbs' controlling and uncaring boss, the CEO of Greenway Press.\n* [[Andy Richter]] as Morris, an associate of Walter Hobbs.\n* [[Kyle Gass]] as Eugene Dupree, an associate of Walter Hobbs.\n* [[Artie Lange]] as the Fake Santa, a Mall Santa who Buddy gets into an altercation with due to him not being the real Santa Claus.\n* [[Jon Favreau]] as Dr. Ben Leonardo, the Hobbs family's [[pediatrician]].\n* [[Matt Walsh (comedian)|Matt Walsh]] as Eye Witness.\n* [[Peter Billingsley]] as Ming Ming (uncredited), the head elf of their workshop.\n* [[Mark Acheson]] as a mailroom worker.\n* [[David Paul Grove]] as Pom Pom, an elf who Buddy faints on when he discovers he's a human.\n* Claire Lautier as Charlotte Dennon, NY 1 Reporter.\n* Jane Bradbury as Susan Wells. (only in photograph)\n* Patrick Ferrell as a security guard #1.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n* Patrick McCartney as a security guard #2.\n\n===Voices===\n* [[Leon Redbone]] as Leon the Snowman, a snowman who lives at the North Pole.\n* [[Ray Harryhausen]] as Polar Bear Cub.\n* [[Jon Favreau]] as the Baby Walrus, Mr. [[Narwhal]] and the Arctic Puffin.\n* [[Dallas McKennon]] as the Jack-in-the-Box (archive audio)\n* [[Maurice LaMarche]] as Buddy's Burp (uncredited)\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[David Berenbaum]] initially wrote the script in 1993 with [[Jim Carrey]] in mind to star. <ref>{{cite web |title=10 Things You Didn't Know About Elf |url=https://thefw.com/things-you-didnt-know-about-elf/ |website=TheFW |accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|last=Mullins|first=Jenna|title=NEWS/ 56 Facts You May Not Know About Your Favorite Holiday Films|date=December 18, 2014|work=[[E! News]]|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/607359/56-facts-you-may-not-know-about-your-favorite-holiday-films|accessdate=June 17, 2015}}</ref> Berenbaum's screenplay underwent uncredited rewrites by [[Scot Armstrong]],<ref name=\"Falcon\">{{cite news|last1=Falcon|first1=Jesse|title=Old School's Scot Armstrong|url=http://www.cracked.com/article_15324_3Ci3Eold-schools3Ci3E-scot-armstrong.html|accessdate=November 25, 2017|work=Cracked|date=February 1, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Fritz\">{{cite news|last1=Fritz|first1=Ben|title=Inside Move: Lack of Will power won't stop 'Elf' sequel|url=https://variety.com/2005/film/markets-festivals/inside-move-lack-of-will-power-won-t-stop-elf-sequel-1117924481/|accessdate=November 25, 2017|work=Variety|date=June 14, 2005}}</ref> [[Chris Henchy]],<ref name=\"Riley\">{{cite news|last1=Riley|first1=Jenelle|title=Will Ferrell and Adam McKay Celebrate a Decade of Gary Sanchez Productions|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/features/will-ferrell-and-adam-mckay-gary-sanchez-productions-1201782344/|accessdate=November 25, 2017|work=Variety|date=May 27, 2016}}</ref> and the writing team of [[Adam McKay]] and [[Will Ferrell]].<ref name=\"O'Hara\">{{cite news|last1=O'Hara|first1=Helen|title=Adam McKay: laughing all the way to the bank|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/the-big-short/adam-mckay-interview/|accessdate=November 25, 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=January 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Caro\">{{cite news|last1=Caro|first1=Mark|title='Anchorman 2': The Chicago roots of Adam McKay|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/chi-adam-mckay-anchorman-2-interview-20131206-column.html|accessdate=November 25, 2017|work=Chicago Tribune|date=December 6, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Weiner\">{{cite news|last1=Weiner|first1=Jonah|title=Anchor Management|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/anchor-management-20140228|accessdate=November 25, 2017|work=Rolling Stone|date=February 28, 2014}}</ref> According to Favreau, the script was initially \"much darker\" and did not interest him, although he was interested in working with Ferrell's first post-SNL movie. <ref name=\"Rollingstoneelften\">{{cite web |last1=Susman |first1=Gary |title='Elf' at 10: Jon Favreau Reflects on Buddy's Magical Legacy |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/elf-at-10-jon-favreau-reflects-on-buddys-magical-legacy-187068/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> Asked to rewrite it, a turning point came when he realized he could make Buddy's world an homage to the Rankin Bass Christmas specials. This allowed him to conceive of a movie that could be PG rated as opposed to the original script, which he guessed would have been rated PG-13. <ref name=\"Rollingstoneelften\"/> \n\n[[Terry Zwigoff]] was offered to direct, but declined due to his commitment on another Christmas comedy of 2003, ''[[Bad Santa]].''{{cn|date= November 2017}} [[Jon Favreau]] eventually directed the film.\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Jon Favreau Deauville 2014.jpg|thumb|upright|Director [[Jon Favreau]] in 2014.]]\n\n{{Anchor|Locations}} [[Principal photography]] began on December 2, 2002 and [[Wrap (filmmaking)|wrapped]] on March 7, 2003.<ref name=\"Arnold\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o5pKDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT319&lpg=PT319&dq=elf+filming+2002&source=bl&ots=p1aqdU8gyk&sig=ACfU3U3YXTSjnGi4fNEMuXp8ftZLaZneJQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiZu5bEzqDoAhVmknIEHV7wBucQ6AEwD3oECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=elf%20filming%202002&f=false|title=Christmas in the Movies: 30 Classics to Celebrate the Season|last=Arnold|first=Jeremy|date=2018|publisher=Arnold|isbn=9780786486946|language=en}}</ref> Filming took place in New York City, as well as in Vancouver and at [[Riverview Hospital (Coquitlam)|Riverview Hospital]] in [[Coquitlam]], British Columbia.<ref name=\"rolling-favreau\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hpzr.proboards.com/index.cgi?board=otherc&action=print&thread=2458|title=Explanation of the sound effect|accessdate=October 9, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715114901/http://hpzr.proboards.com/index.cgi?board=otherc&action=print&thread=2458|archivedate=July 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe film makes heavy use of [[forced perspective]] to exaggerate the size of Buddy compared to all the other elves. Stop motion animation was employed for certain sequences.<ref name=\"rolling-favreau\">{{cite magazine|author=Gary Susman |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/elf-at-10-jon-favreau-reflects-on-buddys-magical-legacy-20131224 |title='Elf' at 10: Jon Favreau Reflects on Buddy's Magical Legacy &#124; Movies News |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=December 24, 2013 |accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] usage was kept to a minimum due to Favreau's own preference, something that he would later note he \"had to fight very hard\" for films.<ref name=\"Rollingstoneelften\"/> \n\n{{Anchor|Sound design}} [[Zooey Deschanel]] singing was not in the original script, and Favreau added it when he learned she was a singer.<ref name=\"rolling-favreau\" /> When Buddy starts singing in the middle of Santaland at Gimbels, the lyrics were not scripted and Will Ferrell improvised the song on the spot.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/33059001|title=Will Ferrell in 'Elf\" Interview|website=Vimeo|access-date=April 21, 2016}}</ref> Even though Buddy is an excellent gift wrapper, Will Ferrell is not, and needed someone else to wrap all the gifts in the movie.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Post-production===\nApart from snow, most of the computer generated imagery (CGI) in the film was created by [[Rhythm & Hues Studios]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Stephanie|last=Snipes|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2003/SHOWBIZ/Movies/11/07/sprj.caf03.making.elf/index.html |title=How to create an 'Elf'|work=CNN.com|date=November 7, 2003|accessdate=December 25, 2015|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref> Buddy's belch after drinking a two-liter bottle of [[Coca-Cola]] was real, as dubbed by voice actor [[Maurice LaMarche]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/www.talkradiomeltdown.com/podcasts/4-26-11.mp3|title= Maurice LaMarche interview on Talk Radio Meltdown - Explanation of Buddy the Elf's belch at 21:52|publisher=Talk Radio Meltdown|accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n===Box office===\n''Elf'' grossed $173.4 million in North America and $47 million in other territories for a total gross of $220.4 million, against a budget of $33 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> \n\nThe film opened at number two at the box office in the United States with $31.1 million, finishing behind ''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]'', also in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2003&wknd=45&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office Results for November 7-9, 2003|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|access-date=October 9, 2014}}</ref> It topped the box office on its second week of release, beating out ''[[Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World]]''. In the United Kingdom, it opened in second behind ''[[Love Actually]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Elf beats Crowe at US box office |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/film/3275911.stm |work=bbc.co.uk |publisher= BBC News |date= November 16, 2003 |access-date= December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 84% based on 193 reviews, and an average rating of 7.03/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"A movie full of Yuletide cheer, ''Elf'' is a spirited, good-natured family comedy, and it benefits greatly from Will Ferrell's funny and charming performance as one of Santa's biggest helpers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/elf/|title=Elf (2003)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 64 out of 100, based on 38 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/elf|title=Elf reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=May 31, 2016}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= December 20, 2018 |access-date= July 24, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave it 3 out of 4 stars, calling it \"one of those rare Christmas comedies that has a heart, a brain and a wicked sense of humor, and it charms the socks right off the mantelpiece.\"<ref>{{cite web|last= Ebert |first= Roger |url= http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/elf-2003 |title=Elf Movie Review & Film Summary (2003) |publisher=Roger Ebert |date=November 7, 2003 |accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [[Peter Travers]] gave the film 2 out of 4 stars, saying: \"Ferrell makes the damn thing work. Even though he can't get naked or use naughty words, there's a devil of comedy in Ferrell, and he lets it out to play. Director Jon Favreau has the good sense to just stand out of his way.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Travers |first=Peter |author-link=Peter Travers|title='Elf' review|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/elf-20031107|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=November 7, 2003|access-date=December 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\nThe film was nominated for nine awards and won two.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0319343/awards|title=Elf Awards|website=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=January 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\n'''Won'''\n* 2004 ASCAP award \u2013 Top Box Office Films (John Debney)\n* 2004 Golden Trailer \u2013 Best Comedy\n\n'''Nominated'''\n* 2004 Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Award \u2013 Favorite Movie\n* 2004 MTV Movie Award \u2013 Best Comedic Performance (Will Ferrell)\n* 2004 PFCS Award \u2013 Best Live Action Family Film and Best Use of Previously Published or Recorded Music\n* 2004 Teen Choice Award \u2013 [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Actor - Comedy|Choice Movie Actor \u2013 Comedy]] (Will Ferrell) and [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie - Comedy|Choice Movie \u2013 Comedy]]\n* 2005 Golden Satellite Award \u2013 Best Youth DVD\n\n===Critics' rankings===\n''Elf'' is often ranked among the greatest Christmas films,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heavy.com/social/2015/12/christmas-movies-holiday-films-top-ten-best-rankings-list-netflix-watch-all-time-xmas-elf-its-a-wonderful-life/10/ |title=Christmas Movie Rankings: 10 Best Christmas Movies|work=Heavy.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/12/24/christmas-movies-family-17-holiday_n_2332363.html | work=Huffington Post | title=17 Favorite Christmas Movies | date=December 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/best-christmas-movies-including-home-alone-scrooged-muppet-christmas-carol|title=Best Christmas Movies including Home Alone, Scrooged, Muppet Christmas Carol|author=Dave Infante|date=December 18, 2015|work=thrillist}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/new/10-Greatest-Christmas-Movies-All-Time-According-British-People-68585.html|title=The 10 Greatest Christmas Movies Of All-Time, According To British People|author=|date=|work=cinemablend.com}}</ref> and airs annually on television during the holiday season. In 2017, [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] users rated ''Elf'' the best Christmas film of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movieweb.com/elf-best-christmas-movie-21st-century/|title=Elf Is the Top Christmas Movie of the 21st Century|date=December 22, 2017|website=Movieweb.com}}</ref>\n\n* [[Digital Spy]] \u2013 #3<ref>{{cite news |last=Reynolds|first=Simon|title=Muppet Christmas Carol tops Digital Spy favourite Christmas film poll |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a356141/muppet-christmas-carol-tops-digital-spy-favourite-christmas-film-poll.html |work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|date=December 19, 2011|accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n* ''[[Total Film]]'' \u2013 #3<ref>{{cite web|title=Elf #3 total film greatest xmas film of all time|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/50-best-christmas-movies/elf-2003|website=Totalfilm.com}}</ref>\n* ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' \u2013 #4<ref>{{cite news|title=Entertainment Weekly Greatest xmas movies of all time Elf #4|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20317203_20449281_20888961,00.html#20889033 | first=Chris | last=Nashawaty|website=Ew.com|date=December 26, 2011}}</ref>\n* ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' \u2013 #4<ref>{{cite news|title=SFC Elf #4 Greatest christmas movie of all time|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/thebigevent/2011/12/22/todays-special-best-christmas-movies-of-all-time/#2224101=0 |newspaper=[[The San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Guardian]]'' \u2013 #4<ref>{{cite web|title=Guardian Greatest christmas movies Elf #4|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/nov/29/christmas-favourite-film-poll-wonderful|publisher=HanMan}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' \u2013 #6<ref>{{cite news|title=Elf #6 Greatest xmas film of all time|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/best-christmas-movies-grinch-rudolph-395660#6-elf | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | first=Aaron|last=Couch}}</ref>\n* ''[[Forbes]]'' \u2013 #7<ref>{{cite news|title=Elf #7 Forbes best christmas movies of all time|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2011/12/14/top-ten-best-christmas-movies-of-all-time/ | first=Mark | last=Hughes|website=Forbes.com}}</ref>\n* ''[[Newsday]]'' \u2013 #7<ref>{{cite web|title=Newsday Elf 7th best christmas film|url=http://www.newsday.com/business/press-releases/a-christmas-story-voted-greatest-holiday-movie-of-all-time-1.6567718|website=Newsday.com}}</ref>\n* [[about.com]] \u2013 #9<ref>{{Cite news |title=Top 10 Christmas Movies |url=http://movies.about.com/od/dvds/tp/Best-Christmas-Movies.htm |work=[[About.com]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n* ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' \u2013 #11<ref>{{Cite news |title=The 30 Best Christmas Movies Ever |url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/30-best-christmas-movies/p29 |website=Empireonline.com |publisher=Bauer Consumer Media |date=December 2010 |accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n* ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' \u2013 #17<ref>{{cite news|title=Chicago tribune #17 elf greatest christmas film of all time|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sns-zap-photogallery-top25christmasmovies,0,3752252.photogallery|publisher=HanMan}}</ref>\n* ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' - #23<ref>{{Cite news |title=Merry Christmas! The best Christmas movies ever |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/merry-christmas-best-christmas-movies-gallery-1.10716 |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]|date=December 21, 2011 |accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n{{Anchor|DVD|Video|Home video}}\nThe film was released on [[DVD]] and [[VHS]] on November 16, 2004, and on [[Blu-ray]] on October 28, 2008. It is also available for the [[PlayStation Portable]] with [[Universal Media Disc]]. This is one of the only two DVDs to be PG rated under the ''[[Infinifilm]]'' label.\n\n==Musical==\n{{Anchor|Stage musical}}\n{{main|Elf: The Musical}}\nA [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] [[Musical theatre|musical]] based upon the film ran on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] during the 2010 Christmas season. It was directed by [[Casey Nicholaw]], with music by [[Matthew Sklar]], lyrics by [[Chad Beguelin]], and a book by [[Bob Martin (comedian)|Bob Martin]] and [[Thomas Meehan (writer)|Thomas Meehan]].\n\nThe musical officially opened at the [[Al Hirschfeld Theatre]] on November 10, 2010, after previews from November 2, 2010. The cast included [[Sebastian Arcelus]] as Buddy, [[Amy Spanger]] as Jovie, [[Beth Leavel]] as Emily, Mark Jacoby as Walter, [[Matthew Gumley]] as Michael, Valerie Wright as Deb, Michael McCormick as Mr. Greenway, Michael Mandell as Store Manager, and [[George Wendt]] as Santa. It ran through to January 2, 2011.<ref>Hetrick, Adam.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/141993-Beth-Leavel-Mark-Jacoby-and-George-Wendt-to-Star-in-Elf-The-Musical-on-Broadway \"Beth Leavel, Mark Jacoby and George Wendt to Star in Elf \u2013 The Musical on Broadway\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815122901/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/141993-Beth-Leavel-Mark-Jacoby-and-George-Wendt-to-Star-in-Elf-The-Musical-on-Broadway |date=August 15, 2010 }} playbill.com, August 11, 2010</ref>\n\n==Music==\nThe soundtrack was released on [[New Line Records]] in November 2003 in the United States<ref>{{cite web|title=Elf: Music From The Major Motion Picture|url=https://www.amazon.com/Elf-Music-Major-Motion-Picture/dp/B0000DIZT4|website=Amazon.com|accessdate=December 26, 2017}}</ref> and in October 2005 in the United Kingdom, including its signature song \"[[Baby, It's Cold Outside]]\" by Deschanel and Leon Redbone, releasing it as a single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B000BBGBII|title=Elf Original Soundtrack|website=Amazon.co.uk|accessdate=January 1, 2010}}</ref> It was certified Gold by the [[RIAA]] in April 2011.<ref>{{cite certification|region=United States|title=Elf: Music from the Major Motion Picture|accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref> Having sold 695,000 copies in the United States, it is the second best-selling film soundtrack/holiday album hybrid since [[Nielsen SoundScan]] started tracking music sales in 1991, behind only ''[[The Polar Express (soundtrack)|The Polar Express]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6385927/billboard-200-chart-moves-guardians-on-cassette-cashes-in |title=Billboard 200 Chart Moves: 'Guardians' on Cassette Cashes In |last=Caulfield |first=Keith |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=December 6, 2014 |accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<!-- see [[Template:Soundtrack]] to improve this section -->\n# \"[[Pennies from Heaven (song)|Pennies from Heaven]]\" \u2013 [[Louis Prima]]\n# \"[[Sleigh Ride]]\" \u2013 [[Ella Fitzgerald]] and the [[Frank De Vol]] Orchestra\n# \"[[Let It Snow! Let It Snow! Let It Snow!]]\" \u2013 [[Lena Horne]]\n# \"Sleigh Ride/Santa Claus' Party\" \u2013 [[Ferrante and Teicher]]/[[Les Baxter]]\n# \"[[Baby, It's Cold Outside]]\" \u2013 [[Leon Redbone]]/[[Zooey Deschanel]]\n# \"[[Jingle Bells]]\" \u2013 [[Jim Reeves]]\n# \"[[The Nutcracker Suite]]\" \u2013 [[Brian Setzer]]\n# \"Christmas Island\" \u2013 [[Leon Redbone]]\n# \"[[Santa Baby]]\" \u2013 [[Eartha Kitt]] and the [[Henri Ren\u00e9]] Orchestra\n# \"[[Winter Wonderland]]\" \u2013 [[Leon Redbone]]\n# \"[[Santa Claus Is Coming to Town]]\" \u2013 [[Eddy Arnold]]\n# \"[[Nothing from Nothing (Billy Preston song)|Nothing from Nothing]]\" \u2013 [[Billy Preston]]\n\nThe [[Film score|score to the film]], composed and conducted by [[John Debney]] and performed by the [[Hollywood Studio Symphony]], was released by [[Var\u00e8se Sarabande]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodstudiosymphony.com/cd2.asp?ID=55|title=Hollywood Studio Symphony|website=Hollywoodstudiosymphony.com|accessdate=January 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Animated special==\n{{main|Elf: Buddy's Musical Christmas}}\n''Elf: Buddy's Musical Christmas'' is an hour-long stop-motion animated musical television special based on the film and the [[Elf: The Musical|musical of the same name]]. While Edward Asner was the only cast member from the film to reprise his role, the rest of the cast included [[Jim Parsons]] as Buddy, [[Mark Hamill]] as Walter Hobbs, [[Kate Micucci]] as Jovie, [[Rachael MacFarlane]] as Emily Hobbs, [[Max Charles]] as Michael Hobbs, and [[Gilbert Gottfried]] as Mr. Greenway. It was produced by [[Warner Bros. Animation]] and first aired on [[NBC]] on December 16, 2014. It features songs from the musical.\n\n==Video game==\nA video game based on the film was released on November 4, 2004 for the [[Game Boy Advance]], developed by Human Soft and published by [[Crave Entertainment]].<ref name=\"metacritic.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/game-boy-advance/elf-the-movie|title=Elf: The Movie|website=Metacritic|accessdate=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/gaming/crave-brings-elf-to-gba-for-the-holidays/|title=Crave Brings Elf to GBA for the Holidays|first=Ryan|last=Ball|date=September 23, 2004|website=Animationmagazine.net|accessdate=May 31, 2019}}</ref> The game follows the same plot as the movie; within the game, the player has to collect candies throughout each level while avoiding various objects and polar bears. The game, however, received mixed to negative reviews by critics.<ref name=\"metacritic.com\"/>\n\n==Possible sequel==\nIn September 2013, [[Mental Floss]] reported that Favreau was interested in making a sequel to ''Elf'', entitled ''Elf 2: Buddy Saves Christmas''.<ref>{{cite web|title=55 Unfortunately Unfinished Films|date=September 18, 2013|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/52785/55-unfortunately-unfinished-films|website=Mentalfloss.com}}</ref> Later in December 2013, Ferrell stated that he does not want to make a sequel to ''Elf''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/will-ferrell-will-absolutely-not-make-elf-2-20131220|title=Will Ferrell Says 'Bah Humbug' to 'Elf 2'|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref> In January 2016, Favreau stated that a sequel to ''Elf'' could still happen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orlando-parfitt.tumblr.com/post/142799073508/elf-2-could-happen-says-jon-favreau-exclusive|title=Elf 2 Could Happen Says Jon Favreau (Exclusive)|website=Orlando-parfitt.tumblr.com}}</ref> The next month Ferrell reiterated that a sequel was unlikely, and stated that he was generally reluctant to do sequels unless there was a story that justifies it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/02/11/why-will-ferrell-wont-make-elf-2|title=Why Will Ferrell Won't Make Elf 2|first=Chris|last=Tilly|date=February 11, 2016|website=IGN.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.warnerbros.com/movies/elf/ Official Warner Bros. Site]\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{Amg movie}}\n* {{mojo title}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes}}\n\n{{Jon Favreau}}\n{{Warner Christmas films}}\n[[Category:2003 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s Christmas comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s children's films]] \n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:American Christmas comedy films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films about elves]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:New Line Cinema films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Debney]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jon Favreau]]\n[[Category:Films set in department stores]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Films using computer-generated imagery]]\n[[Category:Films using stop-motion animation]]\n[[Category:Films with live action and animation]]\n[[Category:Santa Claus in film]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2003 comedy film starring Will Ferrell directed by Jon Favreau}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{other uses|Elf (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Elf\n| image = Elf movie.jpg\n| alt = A man dressed like an elf stands between the letters \"''e''\" and \"''f''\".\n| caption = Theatrical release poster\n| director = [[Jon Favreau]]\n| producer = {{plainlist|\n* Jon Berg\n* [[Todd Komarnicki]]\n* [[Shauna Robertson]]\n}}\n| writer = [[David Berenbaum]]\n| starring = {{plainlist| \n* [[Will Ferrell]]\n* [[James Caan]]\n* [[Zooey Deschanel]]\n* [[Mary Steenburgen]]\n* [[Ed Asner|Edward Asner]]\n* [[Bob Newhart]]\n}}\n| narrator = Bob Newhart\n| music = [[John Debney]]\n| cinematography = [[Greg Gardiner]]\n| editing = Dan Lebental\n| studio = [[New Line Cinema]]<br>Guy Walks Into a Bar Productions\n| distributor = [[New Line Cinema]]\n| released = {{film date|2003|11|07}}\n| runtime = 97 minutes<ref name=\"BOM\"/> \n| country = United States<ref name=afi>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/members//catalog/DetailView.aspx?s=&Movie=62716|title=Elf|work=[[American Film Institute]]|accessdate=October 25, 2016}}</ref>\n| language = English\n| budget = $33 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n| gross = $220.9 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=elf.htm |title=Elf (2003) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref> \n}}\n'''''Elf''''' is a 2003 American [[Christmas film|Christmas]] [[comedy film]] directed by [[Jon Favreau]], written by [[David Berenbaum]], and starring [[Will Ferrell]], [[James Caan]], [[Zooey Deschanel]], [[Mary Steenburgen]], [[Daniel Tay]], [[Bob Newhart]] and [[Ed Asner]]. The film centers on Buddy, a human who was adopted and raised by [[Christmas elf|Santa's elves]]. He learns about this and heads to [[New York City]] to meet his biological father while also spreading Christmas cheer in a world of cynics in the process. \n\n''Elf'' was released in the United States on November 7, 2003 by [[New Line Cinema]] to critical and commercial success, grossing $220 million worldwide against a $33 million budget. Ferrell\u2019s performance as Buddy the Elf was praised by audiences and critics alike, with many calling it one of his best performances. It inspired the 2010 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical ''[[Elf (Broadway musical)|Elf: The Musical]]'' and [[NBC]]'s 2014 [[Stop motion|stop-motion]] animated television special ''[[Elf: Buddy's Musical Christmas]]''. It is often listed among the greatest Christmas films of all time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thetoptens.com/top-christmas-movies/|title=Top Ten Christmas Movies Of All Time |website=Thetoptens.com|access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/guide/best-christmas-movies/|title=The 50 Best Christmas Movies of All Time|language=en-US|access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/best-christmas-movies-of-all-time|title=The 50 Best Christmas Movies of All Time|last=Patches|first=Dan Jackson, Matt|date=December 22, 2017|website=Thrillist|access-date=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!--Per WP: FILMPLOT, plot summaries should be between 400 and 700 words.-->\nOn [[Christmas Eve]], a baby boy at an [[orphanage]] crawls into [[Santa Claus]]'s sack as he is captivated by the sight of a [[teddy bear]], and is unwittingly transported back to the North Pole. When he is discovered at the [[Santa's workshop|workshop]], the elves name him Buddy after the brand label on his diaper, and Papa Elf adopts and raises him. Buddy grows up at the North Pole, believing he is an elf and accepted by the elf community, but due to his human size, he is unable to keep up with the other elves and demoted to the demeaning job of toy testing. Soon, Buddy overhears that he is a human, and Papa Elf explains that Buddy was born to Walter Hobbs and Susan Wells and given up for adoption. Susan subsequently died, and Walter, who now works for a children's book publisher at the [[Empire State Building]] in [[New York City]], is unaware of Buddy's existence. To Buddy's horror, Santa reveals that Walter is on the naughty list due to his selfish and unscrupulous demeanor, but suggests Buddy could help redeem him.\n\nBuddy promptly travels to New York and finds his father at work, but even after he mentions Susan Wells, Walter misinterprets him as a dysfunctional [[Singing telegram|christmas-gram]] messenger and has him kicked out of the premises. Inspired by a sarcastic remark from a security guard, Buddy heads to a local [[Gimbels]] department store, where the manager mistakes him for an employee. At the store's Santa Land, he meets Jovie, an unenthusiastic employee with whom he is instantly smitten. After hearing that Santa will be at the store the following day, Buddy jubilantly decorates Santa Land overnight. When Buddy realizes that the Gimbels Santa is not the real Santa, he unmasks him and causes a wild tumult in the store that lands Buddy in jail.\n\nWalter reluctantly bails him out and takes him to a doctor for a [[DNA profiling|DNA test]], which confirms that Buddy is in fact his long-lost son. The doctor convinces Walter to take Buddy home to meet his [[stepmother]] Emily and twelve-year-old [[half-brother]] Michael, believing once he is faced with reality he will drop the \u201celf thing\u201d and move on as a regular adult. Walter and Michael are put off by Buddy's strange behavior, but Emily insists that they care for him until he \"recovers.\" Michael eventually warms up to Buddy after Buddy defends him from a gang of bullies in a snowball fight, and Michael encourages Buddy to ask Jovie on a date, which she accepts. During the date, the two fall in love. \n\nMeanwhile, Walter's company is in trouble after their most recent book fails to sell. Walter's boss, Fulton Greenway, lays down a hard deadline for Walter to have a new book ready by Christmas Eve. In desperation, Walter and his team secure a meeting with best-selling children's author Miles Finch. Buddy interrupts the meeting to boast of his newfound love and mistakes Finch, who has [[dwarfism]], for an elf. Buddy unintentionally insults Finch and pesters him into losing his temper. An angered and insulted Finch attacks Buddy and walks out on Walter, who snaps in anger at Buddy for ruining the meeting and harshly disowns him. Heartbroken, Buddy leaves a note for Walter, Emily, and Michael on an [[Etch A Sketch]] and wanders about in the streets, lamenting that he does not fit in anywhere.\n\nOn Christmas Eve, after finding Finch's notebook full of ideas, Walter and his team scramble to create a book to pitch. As Walter prepares to pitch the book to Greenway that evening, Michael, who found Buddy's note, arrives and informs Walter that Buddy is gone. Realizing he was wrong and forced to choose between his job or his family, Walter confronts Greenway and despite being fired, leaves with Michael to find Buddy.\n\nAs Buddy wanders the streets, he watches Santa's sleigh crash in [[Central Park]], attracting a large crowd. Buddy tracks down Santa, who explains that the sleigh has lost its engine and cannot fly without it due to a shortage of Christmas spirit. Buddy finds the engine and is reunited with Walter and Michael. Walter apologizes to Buddy and accepts him as his son. Buddy then takes them to meet Santa, who proves himself to Michael by showing him what he truly wanted for Christmas. Michael takes Santa's list and reads it in front of television news cameras gathered outside the park, proving that Santa Claus is real. The Central Park Rangers, who have a grudge against Santa for placing them on the naughty list, chase the sleigh as Buddy tries to reattach the engine. Jovie leads the crowd in singing \"[[Santa Claus Is Coming to Town]],\" helping raise enough Christmas spirit to fully power the sleigh without the engine for the first time in years.\n\nBy the next Christmas, Walter starts his own publishing company with a best-selling book about Buddy's adventures. Buddy and Jovie, now married, bring their newborn daughter Susie to visit Papa Elf.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Will Ferrell]] as Buddy Hobbs, aka \"Buddy the Elf\", an eccentric human who was raised by Santa's elves.\n* [[James Caan]] as Walter Hobbs, a children's book publisher and Buddy's biological father.\n* [[Zooey Deschanel]] as Jovie, an unenthusiastic worker at [[Gimbels]] and Buddy's love interest.\n* [[Mary Steenburgen]] as Emily Hobbs, Walter's wife, Michael's mother and Buddy's stepmother.\n* [[Daniel Tay]] as Michael Hobbs, Walter and Emily's son and Buddy's younger half brother.\n* [[Bob Newhart]] as Papa Elf, Buddy\u2019s adoptive father.\n* [[Ed Asner]] as [[Santa Claus]], who finds Buddy in his sack and gives him to Papa Elf to raise.\n* [[Faizon Love]] as Wanda, the manager of Gimbels and Jovie's boss.\n* [[Peter Dinklage]] as Miles Finch, a best-selling children's author who attacks Buddy for (mistakenly) calling him an elf.\n* [[Amy Sedaris]] as Deb, Walter Hobbs' secretary.\n* [[Michael Lerner (actor)|Michael Lerner]] as Mr. Greenway, Walter Hobbs' controlling and uncaring boss, the CEO of Greenway Press.\n* [[Andy Richter]] as Morris, an associate of Walter Hobbs.\n* [[Kyle Gass]] as Eugene Dupree, an associate of Walter Hobbs.\n* [[Artie Lange]] as the Fake Santa, a Mall Santa who Buddy gets into an altercation with due to him not being the real Santa Claus.\n* [[Jon Favreau]] as Dr. Ben Leonardo, the Hobbs family's [[pediatrician]].\n* [[Matt Walsh (comedian)|Matt Walsh]] as Eye Witness.\n* [[Peter Billingsley]] as Ming Ming (uncredited), the head elf of their workshop.\n* [[Mark Acheson]] as a mailroom worker.\n* [[David Paul Grove]] as Pom Pom, an elf who Buddy faints on when he discovers he's a human.\n* Claire Lautier as Charlotte Dennon, NY 1 Reporter.\n* Jane Bradbury as Susan Wells. (only in photograph)\n* Patrick Ferrell as a security guard #1.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n* Patrick McCartney as a security guard #2.\n\n===Voices===\n* [[Leon Redbone]] as Leon the Snowman, a snowman who lives at the North Pole.\n* [[Ray Harryhausen]] as Polar Bear Cub.\n* [[Jon Favreau]] as the Baby Walrus, Mr. [[Narwhal]] and the Arctic Puffin.\n* [[Dallas McKennon]] as the Jack-in-the-Box (archive audio)\n* [[Maurice LaMarche]] as Buddy's Burp (uncredited)\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[David Berenbaum]] initially wrote the script in 1993 with [[Jim Carrey]] in mind to star. <ref>{{cite web |title=10 Things You Didn't Know About Elf |url=https://thefw.com/things-you-didnt-know-about-elf/ |website=TheFW |accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|last=Mullins|first=Jenna|title=NEWS/ 56 Facts You May Not Know About Your Favorite Holiday Films|date=December 18, 2014|work=[[E! News]]|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/607359/56-facts-you-may-not-know-about-your-favorite-holiday-films|accessdate=June 17, 2015}}</ref> Berenbaum's screenplay underwent uncredited rewrites by [[Scot Armstrong]],<ref name=\"Falcon\">{{cite news|last1=Falcon|first1=Jesse|title=Old School's Scot Armstrong|url=http://www.cracked.com/article_15324_3Ci3Eold-schools3Ci3E-scot-armstrong.html|accessdate=November 25, 2017|work=Cracked|date=February 1, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"Fritz\">{{cite news|last1=Fritz|first1=Ben|title=Inside Move: Lack of Will power won't stop 'Elf' sequel|url=https://variety.com/2005/film/markets-festivals/inside-move-lack-of-will-power-won-t-stop-elf-sequel-1117924481/|accessdate=November 25, 2017|work=Variety|date=June 14, 2005}}</ref> [[Chris Henchy]],<ref name=\"Riley\">{{cite news|last1=Riley|first1=Jenelle|title=Will Ferrell and Adam McKay Celebrate a Decade of Gary Sanchez Productions|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/features/will-ferrell-and-adam-mckay-gary-sanchez-productions-1201782344/|accessdate=November 25, 2017|work=Variety|date=May 27, 2016}}</ref> and the writing team of [[Adam McKay]] and [[Will Ferrell]].<ref name=\"O'Hara\">{{cite news|last1=O'Hara|first1=Helen|title=Adam McKay: laughing all the way to the bank|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/the-big-short/adam-mckay-interview/|accessdate=November 25, 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=January 17, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Caro\">{{cite news|last1=Caro|first1=Mark|title='Anchorman 2': The Chicago roots of Adam McKay|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/chi-adam-mckay-anchorman-2-interview-20131206-column.html|accessdate=November 25, 2017|work=Chicago Tribune|date=December 6, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Weiner\">{{cite news|last1=Weiner|first1=Jonah|title=Anchor Management|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/anchor-management-20140228|accessdate=November 25, 2017|work=Rolling Stone|date=February 28, 2014}}</ref> According to Favreau, the script was initially \"much darker\" and did not interest him, although he was interested in working with Ferrell's first post-SNL movie. <ref name=\"Rollingstoneelften\">{{cite web |last1=Susman |first1=Gary |title='Elf' at 10: Jon Favreau Reflects on Buddy's Magical Legacy |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-news/elf-at-10-jon-favreau-reflects-on-buddys-magical-legacy-187068/ |website=Rolling Stone |accessdate=30 November 2019}}</ref> Asked to rewrite it, a turning point came when he realized he could make Buddy's world an homage to the Rankin Bass Christmas specials. This allowed him to conceive of a movie that could be PG rated as opposed to the original script, which he guessed would have been rated PG-13. <ref name=\"Rollingstoneelften\"/> \n\n[[Terry Zwigoff]] was offered to direct, but declined due to his commitment on another Christmas comedy of 2003, ''[[Bad Santa]].''{{cn|date= November 2017}} [[Jon Favreau]] eventually directed the film.\n\n===Filming===\n[[File:Jon Favreau Deauville 2014.jpg|thumb|upright|Director [[Jon Favreau]] in 2014.]]\n\n{{Anchor|Locations}} [[Principal photography]] began on December 2, 2002 and [[Wrap (filmmaking)|wrapped]] on March 7, 2003.<ref name=\"Arnold\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o5pKDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT319&lpg=PT319&dq=elf+filming+2002&source=bl&ots=p1aqdU8gyk&sig=ACfU3U3YXTSjnGi4fNEMuXp8ftZLaZneJQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiZu5bEzqDoAhVmknIEHV7wBucQ6AEwD3oECAEQAQ#v=onepage&q=elf%20filming%202002&f=false|title=Christmas in the Movies: 30 Classics to Celebrate the Season|last=Arnold|first=Jeremy|date=2018|publisher=Arnold|isbn=9780786486946|language=en}}</ref> Filming took place in New York City, as well as in Vancouver and at [[Riverview Hospital (Coquitlam)|Riverview Hospital]] in [[Coquitlam]], British Columbia.<ref name=\"rolling-favreau\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://hpzr.proboards.com/index.cgi?board=otherc&action=print&thread=2458|title=Explanation of the sound effect|accessdate=October 9, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110715114901/http://hpzr.proboards.com/index.cgi?board=otherc&action=print&thread=2458|archivedate=July 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe film makes heavy use of [[forced perspective]] to exaggerate the size of Buddy compared to all the other elves. Stop motion animation was employed for certain sequences.<ref name=\"rolling-favreau\">{{cite magazine|author=Gary Susman |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/elf-at-10-jon-favreau-reflects-on-buddys-magical-legacy-20131224 |title='Elf' at 10: Jon Favreau Reflects on Buddy's Magical Legacy &#124; Movies News |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=December 24, 2013 |accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> [[Computer-generated imagery|CGI]] usage was kept to a minimum due to Favreau's own preference, something that he would later note he \"had to fight very hard\" for films.<ref name=\"Rollingstoneelften\"/> \n\n{{Anchor|Sound design}} [[Zooey Deschanel]] singing was not in the original script, and Favreau added it when he learned she was a singer.<ref name=\"rolling-favreau\" /> When Buddy starts singing in the middle of Santaland at Gimbels, the lyrics were not scripted and Will Ferrell improvised the song on the spot.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://vimeo.com/33059001|title=Will Ferrell in 'Elf\" Interview|website=Vimeo|access-date=April 21, 2016}}</ref> Even though Buddy is an excellent gift wrapper, Will Ferrell is not, and needed someone else to wrap all the gifts in the movie.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Post-production===\nApart from snow, most of the computer generated imagery (CGI) in the film was created by [[Rhythm & Hues Studios]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Stephanie|last=Snipes|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2003/SHOWBIZ/Movies/11/07/sprj.caf03.making.elf/index.html |title=How to create an 'Elf'|work=CNN.com|date=November 7, 2003|accessdate=December 25, 2015|publisher=[[CNN]]}}</ref> Buddy's belch after drinking a two-liter bottle of [[Coca-Cola]] was real, as dubbed by voice actor [[Maurice LaMarche]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.podtrac.com/pts/redirect.mp3/www.talkradiomeltdown.com/podcasts/4-26-11.mp3|title= Maurice LaMarche interview on Talk Radio Meltdown - Explanation of Buddy the Elf's belch at 21:52|publisher=Talk Radio Meltdown|accessdate=May 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n===Box office===\n''Elf'' grossed $173.4 million in North America and $47 million in other territories for a total gross of $220.4 million, against a budget of $33 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> \n\nThe film opened at number two at the box office in the United States with $31.1 million, finishing behind ''[[The Matrix Revolutions]]'', also in its first week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2003&wknd=45&p=.htm|title=Weekend Box Office Results for November 7-9, 2003|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|access-date=October 9, 2014}}</ref> It topped the box office on its second week of release, beating out ''[[Master and Commander: The Far Side of the World]]''. In the United Kingdom, it opened in second behind ''[[Love Actually]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Elf beats Crowe at US box office |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/film/3275911.stm |work=bbc.co.uk |publisher= BBC News |date= November 16, 2003 |access-date= December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 84% based on 193 reviews, and an average rating of 7.03/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"A movie full of Yuletide cheer, ''Elf'' is a spirited, good-natured family comedy, and it benefits greatly from Will Ferrell's funny and charming performance as one of Santa's biggest helpers.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/elf/|title=Elf (2003)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 64 out of 100, based on 38 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/elf|title=Elf reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=May 31, 2016}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\u2013\" on an A+ to F scale.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |title= Cinemascore |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181220122629/https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ |archive-date= December 20, 2018 |access-date= July 24, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Ebert]] gave it 3 out of 4 stars, calling it \"one of those rare Christmas comedies that has a heart, a brain and a wicked sense of humor, and it charms the socks right off the mantelpiece.\"<ref>{{cite web|last= Ebert |first= Roger |url= http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/elf-2003 |title=Elf Movie Review & Film Summary (2003) |publisher=Roger Ebert |date=November 7, 2003 |accessdate=February 21, 2014}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Rolling Stone]]'', [[Peter Travers]] gave the film 2 out of 4 stars, saying: \"Ferrell makes the damn thing work. Even though he can't get naked or use naughty words, there's a devil of comedy in Ferrell, and he lets it out to play. Director Jon Favreau has the good sense to just stand out of his way.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Travers |first=Peter |author-link=Peter Travers|title='Elf' review|url= https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/elf-20031107|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|date=November 7, 2003|access-date=December 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\nThe film was nominated for nine awards and won two.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0319343/awards|title=Elf Awards|website=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=January 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\n'''Won'''\n* 2004 ASCAP award \u2013 Top Box Office Films (John Debney)\n* 2004 Golden Trailer \u2013 Best Comedy\n\n'''Nominated'''\n* 2004 Nickelodeon Kids' Choice Award \u2013 Favorite Movie\n* 2004 MTV Movie Award \u2013 Best Comedic Performance (Will Ferrell)\n* 2004 PFCS Award \u2013 Best Live Action Family Film and Best Use of Previously Published or Recorded Music\n* 2004 Teen Choice Award \u2013 [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie Actor - Comedy|Choice Movie Actor \u2013 Comedy]] (Will Ferrell) and [[Teen Choice Award for Choice Movie - Comedy|Choice Movie \u2013 Comedy]]\n* 2005 Golden Satellite Award \u2013 Best Youth DVD\n\n===Critics' rankings===\n''Elf'' is often ranked among the greatest Christmas films,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://heavy.com/social/2015/12/christmas-movies-holiday-films-top-ten-best-rankings-list-netflix-watch-all-time-xmas-elf-its-a-wonderful-life/10/ |title=Christmas Movie Rankings: 10 Best Christmas Movies|work=Heavy.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/12/24/christmas-movies-family-17-holiday_n_2332363.html | work=Huffington Post | title=17 Favorite Christmas Movies | date=December 24, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thrillist.com/entertainment/nation/best-christmas-movies-including-home-alone-scrooged-muppet-christmas-carol|title=Best Christmas Movies including Home Alone, Scrooged, Muppet Christmas Carol|author=Dave Infante|date=December 18, 2015|work=thrillist}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/new/10-Greatest-Christmas-Movies-All-Time-According-British-People-68585.html|title=The 10 Greatest Christmas Movies Of All-Time, According To British People|author=|date=|work=cinemablend.com}}</ref> and airs annually on television during the holiday season. In 2017, [[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] users rated ''Elf'' the best Christmas film of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movieweb.com/elf-best-christmas-movie-21st-century/|title=Elf Is the Top Christmas Movie of the 21st Century|date=December 22, 2017|website=Movieweb.com}}</ref>\n\n* [[Digital Spy]] \u2013 #3<ref>{{cite news |last=Reynolds|first=Simon|title=Muppet Christmas Carol tops Digital Spy favourite Christmas film poll |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/news/a356141/muppet-christmas-carol-tops-digital-spy-favourite-christmas-film-poll.html |work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|date=December 19, 2011|accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n* ''[[Total Film]]'' \u2013 #3<ref>{{cite web|title=Elf #3 total film greatest xmas film of all time|url=http://www.totalfilm.com/features/50-best-christmas-movies/elf-2003|website=Totalfilm.com}}</ref>\n* ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' \u2013 #4<ref>{{cite news|title=Entertainment Weekly Greatest xmas movies of all time Elf #4|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/gallery/0,,20317203_20449281_20888961,00.html#20889033 | first=Chris | last=Nashawaty|website=Ew.com|date=December 26, 2011}}</ref>\n* ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' \u2013 #4<ref>{{cite news|title=SFC Elf #4 Greatest christmas movie of all time|url=http://blog.sfgate.com/thebigevent/2011/12/22/todays-special-best-christmas-movies-of-all-time/#2224101=0 |newspaper=[[The San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Guardian]]'' \u2013 #4<ref>{{cite web|title=Guardian Greatest christmas movies Elf #4|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/nov/29/christmas-favourite-film-poll-wonderful|publisher=HanMan}}</ref>\n* ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' \u2013 #6<ref>{{cite news|title=Elf #6 Greatest xmas film of all time|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/gallery/best-christmas-movies-grinch-rudolph-395660#6-elf | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | first=Aaron|last=Couch}}</ref>\n* ''[[Forbes]]'' \u2013 #7<ref>{{cite news|title=Elf #7 Forbes best christmas movies of all time|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markhughes/2011/12/14/top-ten-best-christmas-movies-of-all-time/ | first=Mark | last=Hughes|website=Forbes.com}}</ref>\n* ''[[Newsday]]'' \u2013 #7<ref>{{cite web|title=Newsday Elf 7th best christmas film|url=http://www.newsday.com/business/press-releases/a-christmas-story-voted-greatest-holiday-movie-of-all-time-1.6567718|website=Newsday.com}}</ref>\n* [[about.com]] \u2013 #9<ref>{{Cite news |title=Top 10 Christmas Movies |url=http://movies.about.com/od/dvds/tp/Best-Christmas-Movies.htm |work=[[About.com]] |publisher=[[The New York Times Company]] |accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n* ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' \u2013 #11<ref>{{Cite news |title=The 30 Best Christmas Movies Ever |url=http://www.empireonline.com/features/30-best-christmas-movies/p29 |website=Empireonline.com |publisher=Bauer Consumer Media |date=December 2010 |accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n* ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' \u2013 #17<ref>{{cite news|title=Chicago tribune #17 elf greatest christmas film of all time|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sns-zap-photogallery-top25christmasmovies,0,3752252.photogallery|publisher=HanMan}}</ref>\n* ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' - #23<ref>{{Cite news |title=Merry Christmas! The best Christmas movies ever |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/movies/merry-christmas-best-christmas-movies-gallery-1.10716 |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]|date=December 21, 2011 |accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n{{Anchor|DVD|Video|Home video}}\nThe film was released on [[DVD]] and [[VHS]] on November 16, 2004, and on [[Blu-ray]] on October 28, 2008. It is also available for the [[PlayStation Portable]] with [[Universal Media Disc]]. This is one of the only two DVDs to be PG rated under the ''[[Infinifilm]]'' label.\n\n==Musical==\n{{Anchor|Stage musical}}\n{{main|Elf: The Musical}}\nA [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] [[Musical theatre|musical]] based upon the film ran on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] during the 2010 Christmas season. It was directed by [[Casey Nicholaw]], with music by [[Matthew Sklar]], lyrics by [[Chad Beguelin]], and a book by [[Bob Martin (comedian)|Bob Martin]] and [[Thomas Meehan (writer)|Thomas Meehan]].\n\nThe musical officially opened at the [[Al Hirschfeld Theatre]] on November 10, 2010, after previews from November 2, 2010. The cast included [[Sebastian Arcelus]] as Buddy, [[Amy Spanger]] as Jovie, [[Beth Leavel]] as Emily, Mark Jacoby as Walter, [[Matthew Gumley]] as Michael, Valerie Wright as Deb, Michael McCormick as Mr. Greenway, Michael Mandell as Store Manager, and [[George Wendt]] as Santa. It ran through to January 2, 2011.<ref>Hetrick, Adam.[http://www.playbill.com/news/article/141993-Beth-Leavel-Mark-Jacoby-and-George-Wendt-to-Star-in-Elf-The-Musical-on-Broadway \"Beth Leavel, Mark Jacoby and George Wendt to Star in Elf \u2013 The Musical on Broadway\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100815122901/http://www.playbill.com/news/article/141993-Beth-Leavel-Mark-Jacoby-and-George-Wendt-to-Star-in-Elf-The-Musical-on-Broadway |date=August 15, 2010 }} playbill.com, August 11, 2010</ref>\n\n==Music==\nThe soundtrack was released on [[New Line Records]] in November 2003 in the United States<ref>{{cite web|title=Elf: Music From The Major Motion Picture|url=https://www.amazon.com/Elf-Music-Major-Motion-Picture/dp/B0000DIZT4|website=Amazon.com|accessdate=December 26, 2017}}</ref> and in October 2005 in the United Kingdom, including its signature song \"[[Baby, It's Cold Outside]]\" by Deschanel and Leon Redbone, releasing it as a single.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/B000BBGBII|title=Elf Original Soundtrack|website=Amazon.co.uk|accessdate=January 1, 2010}}</ref> It was certified Gold by the [[RIAA]] in April 2011.<ref>{{cite certification|region=United States|title=Elf: Music from the Major Motion Picture|accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref> Having sold 695,000 copies in the United States, it is the second best-selling film soundtrack/holiday album hybrid since [[Nielsen SoundScan]] started tracking music sales in 1991, behind only ''[[The Polar Express (soundtrack)|The Polar Express]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6385927/billboard-200-chart-moves-guardians-on-cassette-cashes-in |title=Billboard 200 Chart Moves: 'Guardians' on Cassette Cashes In |last=Caulfield |first=Keith |work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=December 6, 2014 |accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<!-- see [[Template:Soundtrack]] to improve this section -->\n# \"[[Pennies from Heaven (song)|Pennies from Heaven]]\" \u2013 [[Louis Prima]]\n# \"[[Sleigh Ride]]\" \u2013 [[Ella Fitzgerald]] and the [[Frank De Vol]] Orchestra\n# \"[[Let It Snow! Let It Snow! Let It Snow!]]\" \u2013 [[Lena Horne]]\n# \"Sleigh Ride/Santa Claus' Party\" \u2013 [[Ferrante and Teicher]]/[[Les Baxter]]\n# \"[[Baby, It's Cold Outside]]\" \u2013 [[Leon Redbone]]/[[Zooey Deschanel]]\n# \"[[Jingle Bells]]\" \u2013 [[Jim Reeves]]\n# \"[[The Nutcracker Suite]]\" \u2013 [[Brian Setzer]]\n# \"Christmas Island\" \u2013 [[Leon Redbone]]\n# \"[[Santa Baby]]\" \u2013 [[Eartha Kitt]] and the [[Henri Ren\u00e9]] Orchestra\n# \"[[Winter Wonderland]]\" \u2013 [[Leon Redbone]]\n# \"[[Santa Claus Is Coming to Town]]\" \u2013 [[Eddy Arnold]]\n# \"[[Nothing from Nothing (Billy Preston song)|Nothing from Nothing]]\" \u2013 [[Billy Preston]]\n\nThe [[Film score|score to the film]], composed and conducted by [[John Debney]] and performed by the [[Hollywood Studio Symphony]], was released by [[Var\u00e8se Sarabande]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodstudiosymphony.com/cd2.asp?ID=55|title=Hollywood Studio Symphony|website=Hollywoodstudiosymphony.com|accessdate=January 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Animated special==\n{{main|Elf: Buddy's Musical Christmas}}\n''Elf: Buddy's Musical Christmas'' is an hour-long stop-motion animated musical television special based on the film and the [[Elf: The Musical|musical of the same name]]. While Edward Asner was the only cast member from the film to reprise his role, the rest of the cast included [[Jim Parsons]] as Buddy, [[Mark Hamill]] as Walter Hobbs, [[Kate Micucci]] as Jovie, [[Rachael MacFarlane]] as Emily Hobbs, [[Max Charles]] as Michael Hobbs, and [[Gilbert Gottfried]] as Mr. Greenway. It was produced by [[Warner Bros. Animation]] and first aired on [[NBC]] on December 16, 2014. It features songs from the musical.\n\n==Video game==\nA video game based on the film was released on November 4, 2004 for the [[Game Boy Advance]], developed by Human Soft and published by [[Crave Entertainment]].<ref name=\"metacritic.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/game-boy-advance/elf-the-movie|title=Elf: The Movie|website=Metacritic|accessdate=May 31, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animationmagazine.net/gaming/crave-brings-elf-to-gba-for-the-holidays/|title=Crave Brings Elf to GBA for the Holidays|first=Ryan|last=Ball|date=September 23, 2004|website=Animationmagazine.net|accessdate=May 31, 2019}}</ref> The game follows the same plot as the movie; within the game, the player has to collect candies throughout each level while avoiding various objects and polar bears. The game, however, received mixed to negative reviews by critics.<ref name=\"metacritic.com\"/>\n\n==Possible sequel==\nIn September 2013, [[Mental Floss]] reported that Favreau was interested in making a sequel to ''Elf'', entitled ''Elf 2: Buddy Saves Christmas''.<ref>{{cite web|title=55 Unfortunately Unfinished Films|date=September 18, 2013|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/52785/55-unfortunately-unfinished-films|website=Mentalfloss.com}}</ref> Later in December 2013, Ferrell stated that he does not want to make a sequel to ''Elf''.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/news/will-ferrell-will-absolutely-not-make-elf-2-20131220|title=Will Ferrell Says 'Bah Humbug' to 'Elf 2'|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]}}</ref> In January 2016, Favreau stated that a sequel to ''Elf'' could still happen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orlando-parfitt.tumblr.com/post/142799073508/elf-2-could-happen-says-jon-favreau-exclusive|title=Elf 2 Could Happen Says Jon Favreau (Exclusive)|website=Orlando-parfitt.tumblr.com}}</ref> The next month Ferrell reiterated that a sequel was unlikely, and stated that he was generally reluctant to do sequels unless there was a story that justifies it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/02/11/why-will-ferrell-wont-make-elf-2|title=Why Will Ferrell Won't Make Elf 2|first=Chris|last=Tilly|date=February 11, 2016|website=IGN.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [https://www.warnerbros.com/movies/elf/ Official Warner Bros. Site]\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{Amg movie}}\n* {{mojo title}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes}}\n\n{{Jon Favreau}}\n{{Warner Christmas films}}\n[[Category:2003 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:2000s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s Christmas comedy films]]\n[[Category:2000s children's films]] \n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's comedy films]]\n[[Category:American Christmas comedy films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films about elves]]\n[[Category:2000s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:New Line Cinema films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by John Debney]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Jon Favreau]]\n[[Category:Films set in department stores]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Films using computer-generated imagery]]\n[[Category:Films using stop-motion animation]]\n[[Category:Films with live action and animation]]\n[[Category:Santa Claus in film]]\n", "name_user": "2600:387:1:809::97", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fixed typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elf_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Baby boomers", "text_new": "{{short description|Generation born during the Post\u2013World War II baby boom; with birth dates generally from 1946 to 1964}}\n{{Redirect|Baby Boomer|the video game|Baby Boomer (video game)|further information|Post\u2013World War II baby boom}}\n{{globalize|date=February 2020}}\n{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Generations Sidebar}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n'''Baby boomers''' are the [[demography|demographic]] [[Cohort (statistics)|cohort]] following the [[Silent Generation]] and preceding [[Generation X]]. The [[generation]] is most often defined as individuals born between 1946 and 1964, during the [[post\u2013World War II baby boom]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sheehan |first1=Paul |title=Greed of boomers led us to a total bust |url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/greed-of-boomers-led-us-to-a-total-bust-20110925-1krki.html |accessdate=21 May 2019 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521015111/https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/greed-of-boomers-led-us-to-a-total-bust-20110925-1krki.html?js-chunk-not-found-refresh=true |archivedate=21 May 2019}}</ref> though some sources cite the cut-off point as early as 1961. The baby boom has been described variously as a \"shockwave\"<ref name=Owram1997>{{Citation | last = Owram | first = Doug | year = 1997 | title = Born at the Right Time | isbn = 0-8020-8086-3 | publisher = Univ Of Toronto Press | location = Toronto | page = [https://archive.org/details/bornatrighttimeh0000owra/page/ x] | url = https://archive.org/details/bornatrighttimeh0000owra/page/ }}</ref> and as \"the pig in the python\";<ref name=Jones1980>{{Citation| last = Jones | first = Landon| year = 1980| title = Great Expectations: America and the Baby Boom Generation| publisher = Coward, McCann and Geoghegan| location = New York}}</ref> in particular, 76 million Americans were born during this timeframe.\n\nIn the 1960s and 1970s, as this relatively large number of young people entered their teens and young adulthood\u2014the oldest turned 18 in 1964\u2014they, and those around them, created a very specific [[rhetoric]] around their cohort and the changes brought about by their size in numbers, such as the [[counterculture of the 1960s]].<ref name=Owram1997a>{{Citation\n | last = Owram\n | first = Doug\n | year = 1997\n | title = Born at the Right Time\n | isbn = 0-8020-8086-3\n | publisher = Univ Of Toronto Press\n | location = Toronto\n | page = [https://archive.org/details/bornatrighttimeh0000owra/page/ xi]\n | url = https://archive.org/details/bornatrighttimeh0000owra/page/\n }}</ref> This rhetoric had an important impact in the perceptions of the boomers, as well as society's increasingly common tendency to define the world in terms of generations, which was a relatively new phenomenon. As a group, baby boomers were wealthier, more active and more physically fit than any preceding generation and were the first to grow up genuinely expecting the world to improve with time.<ref name=\"Jones1980\"/> However, this generation also has been criticized often for its increases in [[consumerism]] which others saw as excessive.<ref name=Pinker>{{cite book |last=Pinker |first=Steven |year=2011 |title=The Better Angels Of Our Nature |location=P.524 |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-141-03464-5}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term [[baby boom]] refers to a noticeable increase in the birth rate. The post-[[World War II]] population increase was described as a \"boom\" by various newspaper reporters, including Sylvia F. Porter in a column in the May 4, 1951, edition of the ''[[New York Post]]'', based on the increase of 2,357,000 in the population of the U.S. in 1950.<ref>''Reader's Digest'' August 1951 pg. 5</ref> \n\nThe first recorded use of \"baby boomer\" is in a January 1963 ''[[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]]'' article describing a massive surge of college enrollments approaching as the oldest boomers were coming of age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/542159/how-generations-named-baby-boomers-generation-x-millennials|title=How Baby Boomers, Generation X, and Millennials Got Their Names|date=May 1, 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Nason |first1=Leslie J. |title=Baby Boomers, Grown Up, Storm Ivy-Covered Walls |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19690752/daily_press/ |accessdate=28 March 2019 |work=Daily Press |date=28 January 1963 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328230347/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19690752/daily_press/ |archivedate=28 March 2019 |location=Newport, Virginia}}</ref>  The ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' dates the modern meaning of the term to a January 23, 1970, article in ''[[The Washington Post]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=baby boomer |work=Oxford English Dictionary |date=1974}}</ref>\n\n== Date range and definitions ==\n[[Pew Research Center]] defines baby boomers as being born between 1946 and 1964.<ref>{{cite news|title=Defining generations: Where Millennials end and post-Millennials begin|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/03/01/defining-generations-where-millennials-end-and-post-millennials-begin|accessdate=May 8, 2018|publisher=Pew Research Center|date=March 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe [[United States Census Bureau]] defines baby boomers as \"individuals born in the United States between mid-1946 and mid-1964.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Colby |first1=Sandra L. |last2=Ortman |first2=Jennifer M. |title=The Baby Boom Cohort in the United States: 2012 to 2060 |url=https://www.census.gov/prod/2014pubs/p25-1141.pdf |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=18 March 2019 |date=May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bump |first1=Philip |title=Here Is When Each Generation Begins and Ends, According to Facts |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2014/03/here-is-when-each-generation-begins-and-ends-according-to-facts/359589/ |accessdate=18 March 2019 |work=The Atlantic |date=25 March 2014}}</ref> [[File:US Birth Rates.svg|thumb|350px|right|United States birth rate (births per 1,000 population per year). The segment for the years 1946 to 1964 is highlighted in red, with birth rates peaking in 1949 and dropping steadily around 1958 reaching pre-war Depression-era levels in 1963.<ref name=\"CDC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/products/vsus/vsus_1980_2003.htm |title=Vital Statistics of the United States: 1980-2003 |work=Table 1-1. Live births, birth rates, and fertility rates, by race: United States, 1909-2003 |publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention/National Center for Health Statistics |accessdate=2019-12-08 }}</ref>]]\n\nThe [[Federal Reserve Board]] uses 1946-1964 to define baby boomers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Distribution of Household Wealth in the U.S. since 1989|url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/releases/z1/dataviz/dfa/distribute/table/#quarter:119;series:Net%20worth;demographic:age;population:all;units:shares|accessdate= 4 January 2020|publisher=Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System|date=23 December 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn the US, the generation can be segmented into two broadly defined cohorts: the \"Leading-Edge Baby Boomers\" are individuals born between 1946 and 1955, those who came of age during the [[Vietnam War]] era. This group represents slightly more than half of the generation, or roughly 38,002,000 people of all races. \n\nThe other half of the generation, called the \"Late Boomers\" or \"Trailing-Edge Boomers\", was born between 1956 and 1964. This second cohort includes about 37,818,000 individuals, according to ''Live Births by Age and Mother and Race, 1933\u201398'', published by the Centers for Disease Control's National Center for Health Statistics.<ref>{{Cite book |first=Brent |last=Green |title=Marketing to Leading-Edge Baby Boomers: Perceptions, Principles, Practices, Predictions |year=2006 |publisher=Paramount Market Publishing |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/marketingtoleadi0000gree_a7w2/page/4 4\u20135] |isbn=0976697351 |url=https://archive.org/details/marketingtoleadi0000gree_a7w2/page/4 }}</ref>\n\nVarious authors have delimited the baby boom period differently. [[Landon Jones]], in his book ''Great Expectations: America and the Baby Boom Generation'' (1980), defined the span of the baby-boom generation as extending from 1946 through 1964.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jones |first1=Landon Y. |title=How 'baby boomers' took over the world |url=https://www.lannyjones.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/How-%E2%80%98baby-boomers%E2%80%99-took-over-the-world-The-Washington-Post.pdf |accessdate=28 March 2019 |work=The Washington Post |date=6 November 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328225337/https://www.lannyjones.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/How-%E2%80%98baby-boomers%E2%80%99-took-over-the-world-The-Washington-Post.pdf |archivedate=28 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nAuthors [[William Strauss]] and [[Neil Howe]], in their 1991 book ''Generations'', define the social generation of boomers as that cohort born from 1943 to 1960, who were too young to have any personal memory of World War II, but old enough to remember the [[History of the United States (1945\u20131964)|postwar American High]] before [[John F. Kennedy]]'s [[Assassination of John F. Kennedy|asassination]].<ref>{{Cite book |first1=Neil |last1=Howe |first2=William |last2=Strauss |title=Generations: The History of Americas Future, 1584 to 2069 |year=1991 |publisher=William Morrow |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/generationshisto00stra_0/page/299 299\u2013316] |isbn=0-688-11912-3 |url=https://archive.org/details/generationshisto00stra_0/page/299 }}</ref> \n\nIn Australia, the [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]] defines baby boomers as those born between 1946 and 1964,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/0/1CD2B1952AFC5E7ACA257298000F2E76?OpenDocument|title=POPULATION BY AGE AND SEX, AUSTRALIA, STATES AND TERRITORIES|date=20 December 2018|accessdate=18 March 2019|publisher=Australian Bureau of Statistics}}</ref> as well as the Australia's Social Research Center which defines baby boomers as born between 1946 and 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.srcentre.com.au/bbqsandblackarmbands/Barbeques%20and%20black%20armbands%20-%20A%20Life%20in%20Australia%20report%20by%20D%20Pennay%20and%20F%20Bongiorno.pdf|title=Barbeques and black armbands: Australians' attitudes to Australia Day|last1=Pennay|first1=Darren|last2=Bongiorno|first2=Frank|date=25 January 2019|publisher=Social Research Center|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref>  [[Bernard Salt]] places the Australian baby boom between 1946 and 1961.<ref name=\"Salt2004\">{{Citation|last=Salt|first=Bernard|title=The Big Shift|year=2004|location=South Yarra, Vic.|publisher=Hardie Grant Books|isbn=978-1-74066-188-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://clrc.gov.au/agd/EMA/rwpattach.nsf/viewasattachmentpersonal/(C86520E41F5EA5C8AAB6E66B851038D8)~1103BookreviewNotesfield.pdf/$file/1103BookreviewNotesfield.pdf|title=The Big Shift|last1=Salt|first1=Bernard|date=November 2003|website=The Australian Journal of Emergency Management|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305125344/http://clrc.gov.au/agd/EMA/rwpattach.nsf/viewasattachmentpersonal/%28C86520E41F5EA5C8AAB6E66B851038D8%29~1103BookreviewNotesfield.pdf/%24file/1103BookreviewNotesfield.pdf|archivedate=5 March 2009|accessdate=28 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Ontario]], Canada, [[David Foot]], author of ''Boom, Bust and Echo: Profiting from the Demographic Shift in the 21st&nbsp;century'' (1997), defined a Canadian boomer as someone born from 1947 to 1966, the years in which more than 400,000 babies were born. However, he acknowledges that that is a demographic definition, and that culturally, it may not be as clear-cut.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Canada |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20060623.dates24/BNStory/BabyBoomers/home |title=By definition: Boom, bust, X and why |work=The Globe and Mail |date=June 24, 2006 |accessdate=2010-08-27 |location=Toronto |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520180757/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20060623.dates24/BNStory/BabyBoomers/home |archivedate=May 20, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nDoug Owram argues that the Canadian boom took place from 1946 to 1962, but that culturally boomers everywhere were born between the late war years and about 1955 or 1956. He notes that those born in the years before the actual boom were often the most influential people among boomers: for example, musicians such as [[The Beatles]], [[Bob Dylan]], and [[The Rolling Stones]], as well as writers like [[Jack Kerouac]] and [[Allen Ginsberg]], who were either slightly or vastly older than the boomer generation. Those born in the 1960s might feel disconnected from the cultural identifiers of the earlier boomers.<ref name=\"Owram1997b\">{{Citation\n | last = Owram\n | first = Doug\n | year = 1997\n | title = Born at the Right Time\n | isbn = 0-8020-8086-3\n | publisher = University Of Toronto Press\n | location = Toronto\n | page = [https://archive.org/details/bornatrighttimeh0000owra/page/ xiv]\n | url = https://archive.org/details/bornatrighttimeh0000owra/page/\n }}</ref>\n\n=== Generational cuspers ===\nThe American term \"[[Generation Jones]]\" is sometimes used to describe those born roughly between 1954 and 1965. The term is typically used to refer to the later years of the baby boomer cohort and the early years of [[Generation X]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/Generation-Jones/145569|title=Not My Generation|last=Williams|first=Jeffrey J.|date=March 31, 2014|website=The Chronicle of Higher Education|url-status=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009033716/https://www.chronicle.com/article/Generation-Jones/145569|archive-date=October 9, 2017|access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fredericknewspost.com/sections/archives/display_detail.htm?StoryID=91159|title=The Frederick News-Post Online \u2013 Frederick County Maryland Daily Newspaper|author=FNP Interactive - http://www.fnpInteractive.com|date=December 19, 2008|publisher=Fredericknewspost.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206110817/http://www.fredericknewspost.com/sections/archives/display_detail.htm?StoryID=91159|archivedate=February 6, 2009|accessdate=2010-08-02}}</ref><ref name=\"AP080111\">Noveck, Jocelyn (2009-01-11), \"In Obama, many see an end to the baby boomer era\".[https://web.archive.org/web/20090125183857/http://www.suntimes.com/news/politics/obama/1372376%2Cw-obama-baby-boomer-era-011109.article].</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nThe [[Ken Dychtwald#Age Wave|age wave]] theory suggests an [[economic slowdown]] when the boomers started retiring during 2007\u20132009.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/ousivMolt/idUSN3131412220080131 Economy faces bigger bust without Boomers], Reuters, Jan 31, 2008</ref> Projections for the [[aging U.S.\u00a0workforce]] suggest that by 2020, 25% of employees will be at least 55 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.cdc.gov/niosh-science-blog/2012/07/agingworkforce/|title=Safer and Healthier at Any Age: Strategies for an Aging Workforce|author=Chosewood, L. Casey|date=July 19, 2012|publisher=National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health|accessdate=2012-07-31}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\n\n=== As children and adolescents ===\nThe baby boomers found that their music, most notably [[rock and roll]], was another expression of their generational identity. [[Transistor radio]]s were personal devices that allowed teenagers to listen to [[The Beatles]], the [[Motown|Motown Sound]], and other new musical directions and artists.\n\nIn the west, baby boomers comprised the first generation to grow up with the [[television]]; some popular boomer-era shows included ''[[Howdy Doody]]'', ''[[The Mickey Mouse Club]]'', ''[[Captain Video]]'', ''[[The Soupy Sales Show]]'', ''[[The Brady Bunch]]'', ''[[Gilligan's Island]]'', ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'', ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'', ''[[Rowan and Martin's Laugh-In]]'', ''[[Star Trek]]'', ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'', ''[[All in the Family]]'' and ''[[Happy Days]]''.\n\n=== As young adults ===\nBoomers grew up at a time of dramatic social change. In the US, that change marked the generation with a strong cultural cleavage, between the proponents of change and the more conservative individuals. Some analysts believe this cleavage played out politically since the time of the [[Vietnam War]] to the mid\u20112000s, to some extent defining the political landscape and division in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/doc/200712/obama|title=Goodbye to all of that|last=Sullivan|first=Andrew|date=November 6, 2007|publisher=Theatlantic.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103235533/http://www.theatlantic.com/doc/200712/obama|archivedate=January 3, 2010<!--DASHBot-->|accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Broder|first=John M.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/21/weekinreview/21broder.html|title=Shushing the Baby Boomers|date=January 21, 2007|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref> \n\nBoomers are often associated with the [[counterculture of the 1960s]], the [[civil rights movement]], and the [[second-wave feminism|\"second-wave\" feminist cause]] of the 1970s. Conversely, many trended in moderate to conservative directions opposite to the counterculture, especially those making professional careers in the military (officer and enlisted), law enforcement, business, blue collar trades, and Republican Party politics. <ref name=\"Isabel Sawhill, Ph.D 2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brookings.edu/views/papers/sawhill/200705.pdf|title=Economic Mobility: Is the American Dream Alive and Well?|author=Isabel Sawhill, Ph.D|author2=John E. Morton|year=2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529155632/http://www.brookings.edu/views/papers/sawhill/200705.pdf|archivedate=May 29, 2013|accessdate=22 March 2013|df=mdy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.urban.org/UploadedPDF/412766-Lost-Generations-Wealth-Building-Among-Young-Americans.pdf|title=Lost Generations? Wealth Building Among Young Americans|last=Steuerle|first=Eugene|author2=Signe-Mary McKernan|year=2013|publisher=Urban Institute|accessdate=22 March 2013|author3=Caroline Ratcliffe|author4=Sisi Zhang}}</ref>\n\nEarly and mid-boomers experienced events like [[Beatlemania]] and [[Woodstock festival|Woodstock]], organizing against the Vietnam War, or fighting and dying in the same war. Politically, early boomers in the United States tend to be [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]s, while later boomers tend to be [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]s.<ref>[http://www.people-press.org/2015/09/03/the-whys-and-hows-of-generations-research/ \"The Whys and Hows of Generations Research\"]. Pew Center. September 3, 2015</ref>\n\n=== In midlife ===\n\n==== Cohort as an economic power ====\nSteve Gillon has suggested that one thing that sets the baby boomers apart from other generational groups is the fact that \"almost from the time they were conceived, boomers were dissected, analyzed, and pitched to by modern [[Marketing|marketers]], who reinforced a sense of generational distinctiveness.\"<ref name=\"Gillon\">Gillon, Steve (2004) ''Boomer Nation: The Largest and Richest Generation Ever, and How It Changed America'', Free Press, \"Introduction\", {{ISBN|0-7432-2947-9}}</ref> \n\nThis is supported by the articles of the late 1940s identifying the increasing number of babies as an economic boom, such as a 1948 ''[[Newsweek]]'' article whose title proclaimed \"Babies Mean Business\",<ref>\"Population: Babies Mean Business\", [https://web.archive.org/web/20051126200640/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/9925897/site/newsweek/ ''Newsweek'', August 9, 1948]. Retrieved 2007-01-26. </ref> or a 1948 ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine article called \"Baby Boom.\"<ref>\"Baby Boom\", [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,856041,00.html ''Time'', February 9, 1948]. Retrieved 2007-01-26.</ref>\n\n==== Conservative uprising ====\nStarting in the 1980s, the boomers became more conservative, many of them regretting the cultural changes they brought in their youth.  The baby boomers became the largest voting demographic in the early 1980s and helped to propel President Reagan into power, a period which ushered in a long running trend of rapidly increasing income inequality. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Bowman|first=Karlyn|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/sep/12/opinion/la-oe-bowman-baby-boomers-more-conservative-20110912|title=As the boomers turn|date=2011-09-12|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=2014-04-13}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1979-2007, those receiving the highest 1 percentile of incomes saw their already large incomes increase by 278% while those in the middle at the 40th-60th percentiles saw a 35% increase. Since 1980, after the vast majority of baby boomer college goers graduated, the cost of college has been increased by over 600% (inflation adjusted).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/general/2013/06/29/how-the-baby-boomers-destroyed-americas-future.aspx|title=How the Baby Boomers Destroyed America's Future|last=Planes|first=Alex|date=June 29, 2013|website=The Motley Fool|publisher=The Motley Fool|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710193649/https://www.fool.com/investing/general/2013/06/29/how-the-baby-boomers-destroyed-americas-future.aspx|archive-date=July 10, 2013|access-date=April 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Attitude towards religion ====\nIn 1993, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine reported on the religious affiliations of baby boomers. Citing Wade Clark Roof, a [[sociologist]] at the [[University of California]] at [[Santa Barbara, California|Santa Barbara]], the articles stated that about 42% of baby boomers were dropouts from formal religion, 33% had never strayed from church, and 25% of boomers were returning to religious practice. \n\nThe boomers returning to religion were \"usually less tied to tradition and less dependable as church members than the loyalists. They are also more liberal, which deepens rifts over issues like [[abortion]] and [[homosexuality]].\"<ref>[[Richard Ostling|Ostling, Richard N.]], \"The Church Search\", April 5, 1993 [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,978164,00.html ''Time'' article retrieved 2007-01-27]</ref>\n\n=== In retirement ===\n\n==== Aging and inheritance planning ====\nA survey found that nearly a third of baby boomer multimillionaires polled in the US would prefer to pass on their [[inheritance]] to [[Charity (practice)|charities]] rather than pass it down to their children. Of these boomers, 57% believed it was important for each generation to earn their own money; 54% believed it was more important to invest in their children while they were growing up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/business/2012/06/half-of-baby-boomers-to-leave-inheritance-to-kids|title=50% of Boomers Leave Estates to Kids|last=News|first=ABC|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|1998}}, it was reported that, as a generation, boomers had tended to avoid discussions and long-term planning for their demise.<ref>[http://milwaukee.bizjournals.com/milwaukee/stories/1998/12/21/focus3.html Baby boomers lag in preparing funerals, estates, etc. The ''Business Journal of Milwaukee'' \u2013 December 18, 1998 by Robert Mullins]. Retrieved 2007-06-18.</ref> However, since 1998 or earlier, there has been a growing dialogue on how to manage aging and end-of-life issues as the generation ages.<ref>[http://www.harvard.edu-ref.com/reporter-s-notebook-kicking-and-screaming-baby-boomers-begin-to-talk-about-aging Article in ''The New York Times'', March 30, 1998] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709033425/http://www.harvard.edu-ref.com/reporter-s-notebook-kicking-and-screaming-baby-boomers-begin-to-talk-about-aging |date=July 9, 2015 }}</ref> \n\nIn particular, a number of commentators have argued that baby boomers are in a state of denial regarding their own aging and death and are leaving an undue economic burden on their children for their retirement and care. According to the 2011 Associated Press and LifeGoesStrong.com surveys:\n\n* 60% lost value in investments because of the economic crisis\n* 42% are delaying retirement\n* 25% claim they will never retire (currently still working)<ref>{{cite web|title=Retirement? For More Baby Boomers, The Answer Is No|url=http://www.thirdage.com/retirement/retirement-for-more-baby-boomers-the-answer-is-no|publisher=ThirdAge Staff|accessdate=June 6, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110721123311/http://www.thirdage.com/retirement/retirement-for-more-baby-boomers-the-answer-is-no| archivedate= July 21, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Redefining Retirement: A Much Longer Lifespan means more to Consider |url=http://www.livingbetterat50.com/redefining-retirement-longer-lifespan-means/|publisher=Living Better at 50|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nPeople often take it for granted that each succeeding generation will be \"better off\" than the one before it. When [[Generation X]] came along just after the boomers, they would be the first generation to enjoy a lower quality of life than the generation preceding it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economicmobility.org/|title=Financial Security and Mobility|website=www.economicmobility.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ellis|first1=David|url=http://money.cnn.com/2007/05/25/pf/mobility_study/index.htm?cnn=yes|title=Making less than dad did|date=2007-05-25|work=CNN|accessdate=2010-05-03}}</ref>\n\n==== Aging and Medicare ====\n{{See also|Aging in the American workforce}}The density of baby boomers can put a strain on [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]]. According to the [[American Medical Student Association]], the population of individuals over the age of 65 will increase by 73 percent between 2010 and 2030, meaning one in five Americans will be a senior citizen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://carrington.edu/blog/medical/baby-boomers-will-affect-health-care-industry-u-s/|title=How baby boomers will affect the health care industry in the U.S. {{!}} Carrington.edu|website=carrington.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-08}}</ref>\n\n==== Aging and online consumption ====\nIn 2019, advertising platform Criteo conducted a survey of 1,000 U.S. consumers which showed baby boomers are less likely than [[millennials]] to purchase groceries online. Of the baby boomers surveyed, 30 percent said they used some form of online grocery delivery service. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/only-30-percent-of-baby-boomers-use-online-grocery-services|title=Baby boomers are less likely than millennials to order groceries online|last=McNulty|first=Matthew|date=2019-11-13|website=FOXBusiness|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\n==Key generation milestones==\nIn the 1985 study of U.S.&nbsp;generational cohorts by Schuman and Scott, a broad sample of adults was asked, \"What world events over the past 50 years were especially important to them?\"<ref>Schuman, H. and Scott, J. (1989), Generations and collective memories, ''American Sociological Review'', vol. 54 (3), 1989, pp. 359\u201381.</ref> For the baby boomers the results were:\n\n* Baby Boomer cohort number one (born 1946\u201355), the cohort who epitomized the cultural change of the 1960s\n** Memorable events: the [[Cold War]] (and associated [[Red Scare]]), the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]], assassinations of [[John F. Kennedy|JFK]], Robert Kennedy, and Martin Luther King, Jr., political unrest, [[Apollo program|walk on the moon]], risk of the draft into the [[Vietnam War]] or actual military service during the Vietnam War, anti-war protests, social experimentation, [[sexual revolution|sexual freedom]], drug experimentation, the [[Civil Rights Movement]], [[environmental movement]], [[Feminism|women's movement]], protests and riots, and [[Woodstock]].\n** Key characteristics: experimental, individualism, free spirited, social cause oriented.\n* Baby Boomer cohort number two (born 1956\u201364), the cohort who came of age in the \"malaise\" years of the 1970s\n** Memorable events: the [[Cold War]], the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] and the assassinations of [[John F. Kennedy]], Robert Kennedy, and Martin Luther King, Jr., for those born in the first couple of years of this generation, the [[Vietnam War]], [[Apollo program|walk on the moon]], [[Watergate scandal|Watergate]] and [[Richard Nixon|Nixon]]'s resignation, lowered drinking age to 18 in many states 1970\u20131976 (followed by raising back to 21 in the mid-1980s as a result of congressional lobbying by [[Mothers Against Drunk Driving]] (MADD)), the [[1973 oil crisis|oil embargo]], raging inflation, gasoline shortages, economic recession and lack of viable career opportunities upon graduation from high school or college, Jimmy Carter's reimposition of registration for the draft, the Iran hostage crisis, [[Ronald Reagan]], [[Live Aid]]\n\n== Legacy ==\nAn indication of the importance put on the impact of the boomer was the selection by ''TIME'' magazine of the Baby Boom Generation as its 1966 \"[[Time Person of the Year|Man of the Year]].\" As Claire Raines points out in ''Beyond Generation&nbsp;X'', \"never before in history had youth been so idealized as they were at this moment.\" When [[Generation\u00a0X]] came along it had much to live up to according to Raines.<ref name=\"beyond\">{{cite book|last=Raines|first=Claire|title=Beyond Generation&nbsp;X|year=1997|publisher=Crisp Publications|isbn=978-1560524496}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|1950s|1960s|Society}}\n\n* [[Me generation]]\n* [[Generation#List of generations|List of generations]]\n* [[Population boom]]\n* [[Generation gap]]\n* [[Transgenerational design]]\n* [[Nano gap]]\n* [[OK Boomer]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Betts|first=David|title=Breaking The Gaze|year=2013|publisher=Kindle|isbn=1494300079}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cheung|first=Edward|title=Baby Boomers, Generation&nbsp;X and Social Cycles, Volume&nbsp;1: North American Long-waves|year=2007|publisher=Longwave Press|isbn=9781896330068}}\n* {{cite book|last=Gibney|first=Bruce  |title=A Generation of Sociopaths: How the Baby Boomers Betrayed America|year=2017|publisher=[[Hachette Books]]|isbn=978-0316395786}}\n* {{cite book|last=Green|first=Brent|title=Marketing to Leading-Edge Baby Boomers: Perceptions, Principles, Practices, and Predictions|year=2006|publisher=Paramount Market Publishing, Inc|location=Ithaca, NY|isbn=978-0976697350|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fQHX8vxKppEC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}\n* {{cite book|last=Green|first=Brent|title=Generation Reinvention: How Boomers Today Are Changing Business, Marketing, Aging and the Future|year=2010|publisher=[[iUniverse]]|location=Bloomington, IN|isbn=978-1-4502-5533-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=H8KPmAEACAAJ&dq=editions:EGFKMerPE6kC}}\n* {{cite book|last=Willett|first=David|title=The Pinch: How the Baby Boomers Took Their Children's Future - and Why They Should Give It Back|year=2011|publisher=Atlantic Books|isbn=9781848872325}}\n* {{cite book|last=Foot|first=David K.|title=Boom Bust & Echo--How to Profit From the Coming Demographic Shift|year=1996|publisher=Macfarlane, Walter & Ross|location=Toronto, Canada|isbn=0-921912-97-8|url=https://archive.org/details/boombustechohowt00foot}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://topics.nytimes.com/top/features/timestopics/series/booming/index.html ''Booming: Living Through the Middle Ages''] - a ''[[New York Times]]'' series about baby boomers\n* {{curlie|Society/People/Generations_and_Age_Groups/Baby_Boomers|Baby Boomers}}\n* [http://www.bonza.com.au/ Baby boomers of New Zealand and Australia]\n* [http://www.cbc.ca/doczone/episodes/boomer-revolution ''Boomer Revolution''], official site\n\n{{Cultural gens}}\n{{Time Persons of the Year 1951\u20131975}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baby boomers}}\n[[Category:Baby boomers| ]]\n[[Category:20th century]]\n[[Category:Cultural generations]]\n[[Category:Demographics]]\n[[Category:Demographics of Australia]]\n[[Category:Demographics of Canada]]\n[[Category:Demographics of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Demographics of the United States]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1950s]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Generation born during the Post\u2013World War II baby boom; with birth dates generally from 1946 to 1964}}\n{{Redirect|Baby Boomer|the video game|Baby Boomer (video game)|further information|Post\u2013World War II baby boom}}\n{{globalize|date=February 2020}}\n{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Generations Sidebar}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2012}}\n'''Baby boomers''' are the [[demography|demographic]] [[Cohort (statistics)|cohort]] following the [[Silent Generation]] and preceding [[Generation X]]. The [[generation]] is most often defined as individuals born between 1946 and 1964, during the [[post\u2013World War II baby boom]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sheehan |first1=Paul |title=Greed of boomers led us to a total bust |url=https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/greed-of-boomers-led-us-to-a-total-bust-20110925-1krki.html |accessdate=21 May 2019 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=26 September 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190521015111/https://www.smh.com.au/politics/federal/greed-of-boomers-led-us-to-a-total-bust-20110925-1krki.html?js-chunk-not-found-refresh=true |archivedate=21 May 2019}}</ref> , though some sources cite the cut-off point as early as 1961. The baby boom has been described variously as a \"shockwave\"<ref name=Owram1997>{{Citation | last = Owram | first = Doug | year = 1997 | title = Born at the Right Time | isbn = 0-8020-8086-3 | publisher = Univ Of Toronto Press | location = Toronto | page = [https://archive.org/details/bornatrighttimeh0000owra/page/ x] | url = https://archive.org/details/bornatrighttimeh0000owra/page/ }}</ref> and as \"the pig in the python\";<ref name=Jones1980>{{Citation| last = Jones | first = Landon| year = 1980| title = Great Expectations: America and the Baby Boom Generation| publisher = Coward, McCann and Geoghegan| location = New York}}</ref> in particular, 76 million Americans were born during this timeframe.\n\nIn the 1960s and 1970s, as this relatively large number of young people entered their teens and young adulthood\u2014the oldest turned 18 in 1964\u2014they, and those around them, created a very specific [[rhetoric]] around their cohort and the changes brought about by their size in numbers, such as the [[counterculture of the 1960s]].<ref name=Owram1997a>{{Citation\n | last = Owram\n | first = Doug\n | year = 1997\n | title = Born at the Right Time\n | isbn = 0-8020-8086-3\n | publisher = Univ Of Toronto Press\n | location = Toronto\n | page = [https://archive.org/details/bornatrighttimeh0000owra/page/ xi]\n | url = https://archive.org/details/bornatrighttimeh0000owra/page/\n }}</ref> This rhetoric had an important impact in the perceptions of the boomers, as well as society's increasingly common tendency to define the world in terms of generations, which was a relatively new phenomenon. As a group, baby boomers were wealthier, more active and more physically fit than any preceding generation and were the first to grow up genuinely expecting the world to improve with time.<ref name=\"Jones1980\"/> However, this generation also has been criticized often for its increases in [[consumerism]] which others saw as excessive.<ref name=Pinker>{{cite book |last=Pinker |first=Steven |year=2011 |title=The Better Angels Of Our Nature |location=P.524 |publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-141-03464-5}}</ref>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe term [[baby boom]] refers to a noticeable increase in the birth rate. The post-[[World War II]] population increase was described as a \"boom\" by various newspaper reporters, including Sylvia F. Porter in a column in the May 4, 1951, edition of the ''[[New York Post]]'', based on the increase of 2,357,000 in the population of the U.S. in 1950.<ref>''Reader's Digest'' August 1951 pg. 5</ref> \n\nThe first recorded use of \"baby boomer\" is in a January 1963 ''[[Daily Press (Virginia)|Daily Press]]'' article describing a massive surge of college enrollments approaching as the oldest boomers were coming of age.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/542159/how-generations-named-baby-boomers-generation-x-millennials|title=How Baby Boomers, Generation X, and Millennials Got Their Names|date=May 1, 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Nason |first1=Leslie J. |title=Baby Boomers, Grown Up, Storm Ivy-Covered Walls |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19690752/daily_press/ |accessdate=28 March 2019 |work=Daily Press |date=28 January 1963 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328230347/https://www.newspapers.com/clip/19690752/daily_press/ |archivedate=28 March 2019 |location=Newport, Virginia}}</ref>  The ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'' dates the modern meaning of the term to a January 23, 1970, article in ''[[The Washington Post]]''.<ref>{{cite news |title=baby boomer |work=Oxford English Dictionary |date=1974}}</ref>\n\n== Date range and definitions ==\n[[Pew Research Center]] defines baby boomers as being born between 1946 and 1964.<ref>{{cite news|title=Defining generations: Where Millennials end and post-Millennials begin|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/03/01/defining-generations-where-millennials-end-and-post-millennials-begin|accessdate=May 8, 2018|publisher=Pew Research Center|date=March 2018}}</ref> \n\nThe [[United States Census Bureau]] defines baby boomers as \"individuals born in the United States between mid-1946 and mid-1964.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Colby |first1=Sandra L. |last2=Ortman |first2=Jennifer M. |title=The Baby Boom Cohort in the United States: 2012 to 2060 |url=https://www.census.gov/prod/2014pubs/p25-1141.pdf |publisher=United States Census Bureau |accessdate=18 March 2019 |date=May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bump |first1=Philip |title=Here Is When Each Generation Begins and Ends, According to Facts |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/national/archive/2014/03/here-is-when-each-generation-begins-and-ends-according-to-facts/359589/ |accessdate=18 March 2019 |work=The Atlantic |date=25 March 2014}}</ref> [[File:US Birth Rates.svg|thumb|350px|right|United States birth rate (births per 1,000 population per year). The segment for the years 1946 to 1964 is highlighted in red, with birth rates peaking in 1949 and dropping steadily around 1958 reaching pre-war Depression-era levels in 1963.<ref name=\"CDC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/nchs/products/vsus/vsus_1980_2003.htm |title=Vital Statistics of the United States: 1980-2003 |work=Table 1-1. Live births, birth rates, and fertility rates, by race: United States, 1909-2003 |publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention/National Center for Health Statistics |accessdate=2019-12-08 }}</ref>]]\n\nThe [[Federal Reserve Board]] uses 1946-1964 to define baby boomers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Distribution of Household Wealth in the U.S. since 1989|url=https://www.federalreserve.gov/releases/z1/dataviz/dfa/distribute/table/#quarter:119;series:Net%20worth;demographic:age;population:all;units:shares|accessdate= 4 January 2020|publisher=Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System|date=23 December 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn the US, the generation can be segmented into two broadly defined cohorts: the \"Leading-Edge Baby Boomers\" are individuals born between 1946 and 1955, those who came of age during the [[Vietnam War]] era. This group represents slightly more than half of the generation, or roughly 38,002,000 people of all races. \n\nThe other half of the generation, called the \"Late Boomers\" or \"Trailing-Edge Boomers\", was born between 1956 and 1964. This second cohort includes about 37,818,000 individuals, according to ''Live Births by Age and Mother and Race, 1933\u201398'', published by the Centers for Disease Control's National Center for Health Statistics.<ref>{{Cite book |first=Brent |last=Green |title=Marketing to Leading-Edge Baby Boomers: Perceptions, Principles, Practices, Predictions |year=2006 |publisher=Paramount Market Publishing |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/marketingtoleadi0000gree_a7w2/page/4 4\u20135] |isbn=0976697351 |url=https://archive.org/details/marketingtoleadi0000gree_a7w2/page/4 }}</ref>\n\nVarious authors have delimited the baby boom period differently. [[Landon Jones]], in his book ''Great Expectations: America and the Baby Boom Generation'' (1980), defined the span of the baby-boom generation as extending from 1946 through 1964.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jones |first1=Landon Y. |title=How 'baby boomers' took over the world |url=https://www.lannyjones.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/How-%E2%80%98baby-boomers%E2%80%99-took-over-the-world-The-Washington-Post.pdf |accessdate=28 March 2019 |work=The Washington Post |date=6 November 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328225337/https://www.lannyjones.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/How-%E2%80%98baby-boomers%E2%80%99-took-over-the-world-The-Washington-Post.pdf |archivedate=28 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nAuthors [[William Strauss]] and [[Neil Howe]], in their 1991 book ''Generations'', define the social generation of boomers as that cohort born from 1943 to 1960, who were too young to have any personal memory of World War II, but old enough to remember the [[History of the United States (1945\u20131964)|postwar American High]] before [[John F. Kennedy]]'s [[Assassination of John F. Kennedy|asassination]].<ref>{{Cite book |first1=Neil |last1=Howe |first2=William |last2=Strauss |title=Generations: The History of Americas Future, 1584 to 2069 |year=1991 |publisher=William Morrow |location=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/generationshisto00stra_0/page/299 299\u2013316] |isbn=0-688-11912-3 |url=https://archive.org/details/generationshisto00stra_0/page/299 }}</ref> \n\nIn Australia, the [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]] defines baby boomers as those born between 1946 and 1964,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/0/1CD2B1952AFC5E7ACA257298000F2E76?OpenDocument|title=POPULATION BY AGE AND SEX, AUSTRALIA, STATES AND TERRITORIES|date=20 December 2018|accessdate=18 March 2019|publisher=Australian Bureau of Statistics}}</ref> as well as the Australia's Social Research Center which defines baby boomers as born between 1946 and 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.srcentre.com.au/bbqsandblackarmbands/Barbeques%20and%20black%20armbands%20-%20A%20Life%20in%20Australia%20report%20by%20D%20Pennay%20and%20F%20Bongiorno.pdf|title=Barbeques and black armbands: Australians' attitudes to Australia Day|last1=Pennay|first1=Darren|last2=Bongiorno|first2=Frank|date=25 January 2019|publisher=Social Research Center|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref>  [[Bernard Salt]] places the Australian baby boom between 1946 and 1961.<ref name=\"Salt2004\">{{Citation|last=Salt|first=Bernard|title=The Big Shift|year=2004|location=South Yarra, Vic.|publisher=Hardie Grant Books|isbn=978-1-74066-188-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://clrc.gov.au/agd/EMA/rwpattach.nsf/viewasattachmentpersonal/(C86520E41F5EA5C8AAB6E66B851038D8)~1103BookreviewNotesfield.pdf/$file/1103BookreviewNotesfield.pdf|title=The Big Shift|last1=Salt|first1=Bernard|date=November 2003|website=The Australian Journal of Emergency Management|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305125344/http://clrc.gov.au/agd/EMA/rwpattach.nsf/viewasattachmentpersonal/%28C86520E41F5EA5C8AAB6E66B851038D8%29~1103BookreviewNotesfield.pdf/%24file/1103BookreviewNotesfield.pdf|archivedate=5 March 2009|accessdate=28 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Ontario]], Canada, [[David Foot]], author of ''Boom, Bust and Echo: Profiting from the Demographic Shift in the 21st&nbsp;century'' (1997), defined a Canadian boomer as someone born from 1947 to 1966, the years in which more than 400,000 babies were born. However, he acknowledges that that is a demographic definition, and that culturally, it may not be as clear-cut.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Canada |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20060623.dates24/BNStory/BabyBoomers/home |title=By definition: Boom, bust, X and why |work=The Globe and Mail |date=June 24, 2006 |accessdate=2010-08-27 |location=Toronto |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090520180757/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/servlet/story/RTGAM.20060623.dates24/BNStory/BabyBoomers/home |archivedate=May 20, 2009 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nDoug Owram argues that the Canadian boom took place from 1946 to 1962, but that culturally boomers everywhere were born between the late war years and about 1955 or 1956. He notes that those born in the years before the actual boom were often the most influential people among boomers: for example, musicians such as [[The Beatles]], [[Bob Dylan]], and [[The Rolling Stones]], as well as writers like [[Jack Kerouac]] and [[Allen Ginsberg]], who were either slightly or vastly older than the boomer generation. Those born in the 1960s might feel disconnected from the cultural identifiers of the earlier boomers.<ref name=\"Owram1997b\">{{Citation\n | last = Owram\n | first = Doug\n | year = 1997\n | title = Born at the Right Time\n | isbn = 0-8020-8086-3\n | publisher = University Of Toronto Press\n | location = Toronto\n | page = [https://archive.org/details/bornatrighttimeh0000owra/page/ xiv]\n | url = https://archive.org/details/bornatrighttimeh0000owra/page/\n }}</ref>\n\n=== Generational cuspers ===\nThe American term \"[[Generation Jones]]\" is sometimes used to describe those born roughly between 1954 and 1965. The term is typically used to refer to the later years of the baby boomer cohort and the early years of [[Generation X]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chronicle.com/article/Generation-Jones/145569|title=Not My Generation|last=Williams|first=Jeffrey J.|date=March 31, 2014|website=The Chronicle of Higher Education|url-status=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009033716/https://www.chronicle.com/article/Generation-Jones/145569|archive-date=October 9, 2017|access-date=January 27, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fredericknewspost.com/sections/archives/display_detail.htm?StoryID=91159|title=The Frederick News-Post Online \u2013 Frederick County Maryland Daily Newspaper|author=FNP Interactive - http://www.fnpInteractive.com|date=December 19, 2008|publisher=Fredericknewspost.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090206110817/http://www.fredericknewspost.com/sections/archives/display_detail.htm?StoryID=91159|archivedate=February 6, 2009|accessdate=2010-08-02}}</ref><ref name=\"AP080111\">Noveck, Jocelyn (2009-01-11), \"In Obama, many see an end to the baby boomer era\".[https://web.archive.org/web/20090125183857/http://www.suntimes.com/news/politics/obama/1372376%2Cw-obama-baby-boomer-era-011109.article].</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nThe [[Ken Dychtwald#Age Wave|age wave]] theory suggests an [[economic slowdown]] when the boomers started retiring during 2007\u20132009.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/ousivMolt/idUSN3131412220080131 Economy faces bigger bust without Boomers], Reuters, Jan 31, 2008</ref> Projections for the [[aging U.S.\u00a0workforce]] suggest that by 2020, 25% of employees will be at least 55 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blogs.cdc.gov/niosh-science-blog/2012/07/agingworkforce/|title=Safer and Healthier at Any Age: Strategies for an Aging Workforce|author=Chosewood, L. Casey|date=July 19, 2012|publisher=National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health|accessdate=2012-07-31}}</ref>\n\n==Characteristics==\n\n=== As children and adolescents ===\nThe baby boomers found that their music, most notably [[rock and roll]], was another expression of their generational identity. [[Transistor radio]]s were personal devices that allowed teenagers to listen to [[The Beatles]], the [[Motown|Motown Sound]], and other new musical directions and artists.\n\nIn the west, baby boomers comprised the first generation to grow up with the [[television]]; some popular boomer-era shows included ''[[Howdy Doody]]'', ''[[The Mickey Mouse Club]]'', ''[[Captain Video]]'', ''[[The Soupy Sales Show]]'', ''[[The Brady Bunch]]'', ''[[Gilligan's Island]]'', ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'', ''[[Batman (TV series)|Batman]]'', ''[[Rowan and Martin's Laugh-In]]'', ''[[Star Trek]]'', ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'', ''[[All in the Family]]'' and ''[[Happy Days]]''.\n\n=== As young adults ===\nBoomers grew up at a time of dramatic social change. In the US, that change marked the generation with a strong cultural cleavage, between the proponents of change and the more conservative individuals. Some analysts believe this cleavage played out politically since the time of the [[Vietnam War]] to the mid\u20112000s, to some extent defining the political landscape and division in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/doc/200712/obama|title=Goodbye to all of that|last=Sullivan|first=Andrew|date=November 6, 2007|publisher=Theatlantic.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100103235533/http://www.theatlantic.com/doc/200712/obama|archivedate=January 3, 2010<!--DASHBot-->|accessdate=2010-08-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Broder|first=John M.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/01/21/weekinreview/21broder.html|title=Shushing the Baby Boomers|date=January 21, 2007|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 31, 2010}}</ref> \n\nBoomers are often associated with the [[counterculture of the 1960s]], the [[civil rights movement]], and the [[second-wave feminism|\"second-wave\" feminist cause]] of the 1970s. Conversely, many trended in moderate to conservative directions opposite to the counterculture, especially those making professional careers in the military (officer and enlisted), law enforcement, business, blue collar trades, and Republican Party politics. <ref name=\"Isabel Sawhill, Ph.D 2007\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brookings.edu/views/papers/sawhill/200705.pdf|title=Economic Mobility: Is the American Dream Alive and Well?|author=Isabel Sawhill, Ph.D|author2=John E. Morton|year=2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529155632/http://www.brookings.edu/views/papers/sawhill/200705.pdf|archivedate=May 29, 2013|accessdate=22 March 2013|df=mdy}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.urban.org/UploadedPDF/412766-Lost-Generations-Wealth-Building-Among-Young-Americans.pdf|title=Lost Generations? Wealth Building Among Young Americans|last=Steuerle|first=Eugene|author2=Signe-Mary McKernan|year=2013|publisher=Urban Institute|accessdate=22 March 2013|author3=Caroline Ratcliffe|author4=Sisi Zhang}}</ref>\n\nEarly and mid-boomers experienced events like [[Beatlemania]] and [[Woodstock festival|Woodstock]], organizing against the Vietnam War, or fighting and dying in the same war. Politically, early boomers in the United States tend to be [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]s, while later boomers tend to be [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]s.<ref>[http://www.people-press.org/2015/09/03/the-whys-and-hows-of-generations-research/ \"The Whys and Hows of Generations Research\"]. Pew Center. September 3, 2015</ref>\n\n=== In midlife ===\n\n==== Cohort as an economic power ====\nSteve Gillon has suggested that one thing that sets the baby boomers apart from other generational groups is the fact that \"almost from the time they were conceived, boomers were dissected, analyzed, and pitched to by modern [[Marketing|marketers]], who reinforced a sense of generational distinctiveness.\"<ref name=\"Gillon\">Gillon, Steve (2004) ''Boomer Nation: The Largest and Richest Generation Ever, and How It Changed America'', Free Press, \"Introduction\", {{ISBN|0-7432-2947-9}}</ref> \n\nThis is supported by the articles of the late 1940s identifying the increasing number of babies as an economic boom, such as a 1948 ''[[Newsweek]]'' article whose title proclaimed \"Babies Mean Business\",<ref>\"Population: Babies Mean Business\", [https://web.archive.org/web/20051126200640/http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/9925897/site/newsweek/ ''Newsweek'', August 9, 1948]. Retrieved 2007-01-26. </ref> or a 1948 ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine article called \"Baby Boom.\"<ref>\"Baby Boom\", [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,856041,00.html ''Time'', February 9, 1948]. Retrieved 2007-01-26.</ref>\n\n==== Conservative uprising ====\nStarting in the 1980s, the boomers became more conservative, many of them regretting the cultural changes they brought in their youth.  The baby boomers became the largest voting demographic in the early 1980s and helped to propel President Reagan into power, a period which ushered in a long running trend of rapidly increasing income inequality. <ref>{{Cite news|last=Bowman|first=Karlyn|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/sep/12/opinion/la-oe-bowman-baby-boomers-more-conservative-20110912|title=As the boomers turn|date=2011-09-12|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=2014-04-13}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1979-2007, those receiving the highest 1 percentile of incomes saw their already large incomes increase by 278% while those in the middle at the 40th-60th percentiles saw a 35% increase. Since 1980, after the vast majority of baby boomer college goers graduated, the cost of college has been increased by over 600% (inflation adjusted).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/general/2013/06/29/how-the-baby-boomers-destroyed-americas-future.aspx|title=How the Baby Boomers Destroyed America's Future|last=Planes|first=Alex|date=June 29, 2013|website=The Motley Fool|publisher=The Motley Fool|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710193649/https://www.fool.com/investing/general/2013/06/29/how-the-baby-boomers-destroyed-americas-future.aspx|archive-date=July 10, 2013|access-date=April 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== Attitude towards religion ====\nIn 1993, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine reported on the religious affiliations of baby boomers. Citing Wade Clark Roof, a [[sociologist]] at the [[University of California]] at [[Santa Barbara, California|Santa Barbara]], the articles stated that about 42% of baby boomers were dropouts from formal religion, 33% had never strayed from church, and 25% of boomers were returning to religious practice. \n\nThe boomers returning to religion were \"usually less tied to tradition and less dependable as church members than the loyalists. They are also more liberal, which deepens rifts over issues like [[abortion]] and [[homosexuality]].\"<ref>[[Richard Ostling|Ostling, Richard N.]], \"The Church Search\", April 5, 1993 [http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,978164,00.html ''Time'' article retrieved 2007-01-27]</ref>\n\n=== In retirement ===\n\n==== Aging and inheritance planning ====\nA survey found that nearly a third of baby boomer multimillionaires polled in the US would prefer to pass on their [[inheritance]] to [[Charity (practice)|charities]] rather than pass it down to their children. Of these boomers, 57% believed it was important for each generation to earn their own money; 54% believed it was more important to invest in their children while they were growing up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/business/2012/06/half-of-baby-boomers-to-leave-inheritance-to-kids|title=50% of Boomers Leave Estates to Kids|last=News|first=ABC|website=ABC News}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|1998}}, it was reported that, as a generation, boomers had tended to avoid discussions and long-term planning for their demise.<ref>[http://milwaukee.bizjournals.com/milwaukee/stories/1998/12/21/focus3.html Baby boomers lag in preparing funerals, estates, etc. The ''Business Journal of Milwaukee'' \u2013 December 18, 1998 by Robert Mullins]. Retrieved 2007-06-18.</ref> However, since 1998 or earlier, there has been a growing dialogue on how to manage aging and end-of-life issues as the generation ages.<ref>[http://www.harvard.edu-ref.com/reporter-s-notebook-kicking-and-screaming-baby-boomers-begin-to-talk-about-aging Article in ''The New York Times'', March 30, 1998] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709033425/http://www.harvard.edu-ref.com/reporter-s-notebook-kicking-and-screaming-baby-boomers-begin-to-talk-about-aging |date=July 9, 2015 }}</ref> \n\nIn particular, a number of commentators have argued that baby boomers are in a state of denial regarding their own aging and death and are leaving an undue economic burden on their children for their retirement and care. According to the 2011 Associated Press and LifeGoesStrong.com surveys:\n\n* 60% lost value in investments because of the economic crisis\n* 42% are delaying retirement\n* 25% claim they will never retire (currently still working)<ref>{{cite web|title=Retirement? For More Baby Boomers, The Answer Is No|url=http://www.thirdage.com/retirement/retirement-for-more-baby-boomers-the-answer-is-no|publisher=ThirdAge Staff|accessdate=June 6, 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110721123311/http://www.thirdage.com/retirement/retirement-for-more-baby-boomers-the-answer-is-no| archivedate= July 21, 2011 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Redefining Retirement: A Much Longer Lifespan means more to Consider |url=http://www.livingbetterat50.com/redefining-retirement-longer-lifespan-means/|publisher=Living Better at 50|accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nPeople often take it for granted that each succeeding generation will be \"better off\" than the one before it. When [[Generation X]] came along just after the boomers, they would be the first generation to enjoy a lower quality of life than the generation preceding it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economicmobility.org/|title=Financial Security and Mobility|website=www.economicmobility.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ellis|first1=David|url=http://money.cnn.com/2007/05/25/pf/mobility_study/index.htm?cnn=yes|title=Making less than dad did|date=2007-05-25|work=CNN|accessdate=2010-05-03}}</ref>\n\n==== Aging and Medicare ====\n{{See also|Aging in the American workforce}}The density of baby boomers can put a strain on [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]]. According to the [[American Medical Student Association]], the population of individuals over the age of 65 will increase by 73 percent between 2010 and 2030, meaning one in five Americans will be a senior citizen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://carrington.edu/blog/medical/baby-boomers-will-affect-health-care-industry-u-s/|title=How baby boomers will affect the health care industry in the U.S. {{!}} Carrington.edu|website=carrington.edu|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-08}}</ref>\n\n==== Aging and online consumption ====\nIn 2019, advertising platform Criteo conducted a survey of 1,000 U.S. consumers which showed baby boomers are less likely than [[millennials]] to purchase groceries online. Of the baby boomers surveyed, 30 percent said they used some form of online grocery delivery service. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/only-30-percent-of-baby-boomers-use-online-grocery-services|title=Baby boomers are less likely than millennials to order groceries online|last=McNulty|first=Matthew|date=2019-11-13|website=FOXBusiness|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-16}}</ref>\n\n==Key generation milestones==\nIn the 1985 study of U.S.&nbsp;generational cohorts by Schuman and Scott, a broad sample of adults was asked, \"What world events over the past 50 years were especially important to them?\"<ref>Schuman, H. and Scott, J. (1989), Generations and collective memories, ''American Sociological Review'', vol. 54 (3), 1989, pp. 359\u201381.</ref> For the baby boomers the results were:\n\n* Baby Boomer cohort number one (born 1946\u201355), the cohort who epitomized the cultural change of the 1960s\n** Memorable events: the [[Cold War]] (and associated [[Red Scare]]), the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]], assassinations of [[John F. Kennedy|JFK]], Robert Kennedy, and Martin Luther King, Jr., political unrest, [[Apollo program|walk on the moon]], risk of the draft into the [[Vietnam War]] or actual military service during the Vietnam War, anti-war protests, social experimentation, [[sexual revolution|sexual freedom]], drug experimentation, the [[Civil Rights Movement]], [[environmental movement]], [[Feminism|women's movement]], protests and riots, and [[Woodstock]].\n** Key characteristics: experimental, individualism, free spirited, social cause oriented.\n* Baby Boomer cohort number two (born 1956\u201364), the cohort who came of age in the \"malaise\" years of the 1970s\n** Memorable events: the [[Cold War]], the [[Cuban Missile Crisis]] and the assassinations of [[John F. Kennedy]], Robert Kennedy, and Martin Luther King, Jr., for those born in the first couple of years of this generation, the [[Vietnam War]], [[Apollo program|walk on the moon]], [[Watergate scandal|Watergate]] and [[Richard Nixon|Nixon]]'s resignation, lowered drinking age to 18 in many states 1970\u20131976 (followed by raising back to 21 in the mid-1980s as a result of congressional lobbying by [[Mothers Against Drunk Driving]] (MADD)), the [[1973 oil crisis|oil embargo]], raging inflation, gasoline shortages, economic recession and lack of viable career opportunities upon graduation from high school or college, Jimmy Carter's reimposition of registration for the draft, the Iran hostage crisis, [[Ronald Reagan]], [[Live Aid]]\n\n== Legacy ==\nAn indication of the importance put on the impact of the boomer was the selection by ''TIME'' magazine of the Baby Boom Generation as its 1966 \"[[Time Person of the Year|Man of the Year]].\" As Claire Raines points out in ''Beyond Generation&nbsp;X'', \"never before in history had youth been so idealized as they were at this moment.\" When [[Generation\u00a0X]] came along it had much to live up to according to Raines.<ref name=\"beyond\">{{cite book|last=Raines|first=Claire|title=Beyond Generation&nbsp;X|year=1997|publisher=Crisp Publications|isbn=978-1560524496}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|1950s|1960s|Society}}\n\n* [[Me generation]]\n* [[Generation#List of generations|List of generations]]\n* [[Population boom]]\n* [[Generation gap]]\n* [[Transgenerational design]]\n* [[Nano gap]]\n* [[OK Boomer]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last=Betts|first=David|title=Breaking The Gaze|year=2013|publisher=Kindle|isbn=1494300079}}\n* {{cite book|last=Cheung|first=Edward|title=Baby Boomers, Generation&nbsp;X and Social Cycles, Volume&nbsp;1: North American Long-waves|year=2007|publisher=Longwave Press|isbn=9781896330068}}\n* {{cite book|last=Gibney|first=Bruce  |title=A Generation of Sociopaths: How the Baby Boomers Betrayed America|year=2017|publisher=[[Hachette Books]]|isbn=978-0316395786}}\n* {{cite book|last=Green|first=Brent|title=Marketing to Leading-Edge Baby Boomers: Perceptions, Principles, Practices, and Predictions|year=2006|publisher=Paramount Market Publishing, Inc|location=Ithaca, NY|isbn=978-0976697350|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fQHX8vxKppEC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage}}\n* {{cite book|last=Green|first=Brent|title=Generation Reinvention: How Boomers Today Are Changing Business, Marketing, Aging and the Future|year=2010|publisher=[[iUniverse]]|location=Bloomington, IN|isbn=978-1-4502-5533-2|url=https://books.google.com/?id=H8KPmAEACAAJ&dq=editions:EGFKMerPE6kC}}\n* {{cite book|last=Willett|first=David|title=The Pinch: How the Baby Boomers Took Their Children's Future - and Why They Should Give It Back|year=2011|publisher=Atlantic Books|isbn=9781848872325}}\n* {{cite book|last=Foot|first=David K.|title=Boom Bust & Echo--How to Profit From the Coming Demographic Shift|year=1996|publisher=Macfarlane, Walter & Ross|location=Toronto, Canada|isbn=0-921912-97-8|url=https://archive.org/details/boombustechohowt00foot}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://topics.nytimes.com/top/features/timestopics/series/booming/index.html ''Booming: Living Through the Middle Ages''] - a ''[[New York Times]]'' series about baby boomers\n* {{curlie|Society/People/Generations_and_Age_Groups/Baby_Boomers|Baby Boomers}}\n* [http://www.bonza.com.au/ Baby boomers of New Zealand and Australia]\n* [http://www.cbc.ca/doczone/episodes/boomer-revolution ''Boomer Revolution''], official site\n\n{{Cultural gens}}\n{{Time Persons of the Year 1951\u20131975}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baby boomers}}\n[[Category:Baby boomers| ]]\n[[Category:20th century]]\n[[Category:Cultural generations]]\n[[Category:Demographics]]\n[[Category:Demographics of Australia]]\n[[Category:Demographics of Canada]]\n[[Category:Demographics of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Demographics of the United States]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1950s]]\n", "name_user": "Hanoi Road", "label": "safe", "comment": "Comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baby_boomers"}
{"title_page": "Resident Evil 2 (2019 video game)", "text_new": "{{short description|Survival horror game by Capcom}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title      = Resident Evil 2\n| image      = Resident Evil 2 Remake.jpg\n| developer  = [[Capcom]]\n| publisher  = Capcom\n| director   = {{Unbulleted list|Kazunori Kadoi|Yasuhiro Anpo}}\n| producer   = {{Unbulleted list|Yoshiaki Hirabayashi|Tsuyoshi Kanda}}\n| designer   = Hidehiro Goda\n| programmer = Masatoshi Fukazawa\n| artist     = {{Unbulleted list|Gez Fry|Satoshi Takamatsu}}\n| composer   = {{Unbulleted list|Shusaku Uchiyama|Zhenlan Kang}}<!--Lead composers only, as per template documentation. -->\n| series     = ''[[Resident Evil]]''\n| engine     = <!--Wikidata-->\n| platforms  = {{Unbulleted list|[[Windows]]|[[PlayStation 4]]|[[Xbox One]]}}\n| released   = January 25, 2019\n| genre      = [[Survival horror]]\n| modes      = [[Single-player]]\n}}\n'''''Resident Evil 2'''''{{efn|{{nihongo|Known in Japan as '''''Biohazard RE:2'''''|\u30d0\u30a4\u30aa\u30cf\u30b6\u30fc\u30c9 RE:2|Baiohaz\u0101do \u0100ru \u012a Ts\u016b|lead=yes}} and commonly referred to as '''''Resident Evil 2 Remake''''' by fans and game journalist while Capcom Officially list the game as a Re-imagining to differentiate from the original.}} is a [[survival horror]] game developed and published by [[Capcom]]. A [[Video game remake|Re-Imagining]] of the 1998 game [[Resident Evil 2|''Resident Evil 2'']], it was released for [[Windows]], [[PlayStation 4]], and [[Xbox One]] on January 25, 2019. Players control rookie police officer [[Leon S. Kennedy]] and student [[Claire Redfield]] as they attempt to escape Raccoon City during a [[zombie apocalypse]].  \n\nCapcom considered remaking ''Resident Evil 2'' following the successful release of [[Resident Evil (2002 video game)|the remake of the first ''Resident Evil'']] in 2002. It was delayed as series creator [[Shinji Mikami]] did not want to divert development from ''[[Resident Evil 4]]'' (2005). Capcom announced the ''Resident Evil 2'' remake in August 2015, and released the first trailer and gameplay footage at [[E3 2018]].\n\n''Resident Evil 2'' received acclaim, with praise for its presentation, gameplay. It was nominated for several awards, including numerous [[game of the year|\"game of the year]]\" awards. By December 2019, it had sold over 5.8 million copies, outselling the original.\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[File:Resident Evil 2 Remake gameplay.png|left|thumb|[[Claire Redfield]] is one of the game's two main playable characters.]]\n''Resident Evil 2'' is a re-imagining of the 1998 game [[Resident Evil 2|of the same name]]. Unlike the original, which uses [[tank controls]] and fixed camera angles, the re-imagining features \"over-the-shoulder\" [[third-person shooter]] gameplay similar to ''[[Resident Evil&nbsp;4]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2018-resident-evil-2-remake-is-familiar-but-ter/1100-6459801/|title=E3 2018: Resident Evil 2 Re-imagining Is Familiar But Terrifying In New Ways|last=Espineli|first=Matt|date=June 12, 2018|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=June 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613084807/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/e3-2018-resident-evil-2-remake-is-familiar-but-ter/1100-6459801/|archive-date=June 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, the standard difficulty mode allows players to save as often as they would like inside safe rooms. If the player chooses to play on \"Hardcore\" difficulty, players will be required to collect and use a finite number of ink ribbons to save the game's progress, much like in the original game.\n\nAs with the original game, the re-imagining of ''Resident Evil 2'' offers the option to play through the main campaign with one of two protagonists, the rookie cop [[Leon S. Kennedy]] or the college student [[Claire Redfield]]. Depending on the player's choice, the main story will be experienced with variations in subplots, accessible areas, and obtainable items.\n\nSimilar to the \"Scenario B\" feature of the original game, beating the main campaign for the first time unlocks the option to play through a \"2nd Run\" as the other protagonist. 2nd Run is a variation of the main campaign that adds additional content to frame the second playthrough as occurring concurrently with the first playthrough. For example, the protagonist in 2nd Run will enter the police station from a different entrance and find several doors already unlocked by the protagonist from the first playthrough. Completing 2nd Run is also required to experience the true ending of the main campaign.\n\n== Plot ==\n{{Long plot|date=March 2020}}\nThe game is set in Raccoon City in September 1998, two months after the events of ''[[Resident Evil (2002 video game)|Resident Evil]]''. Most of the citizens have been turned into mindless creatures, referred to by survivors as zombies, due to an outbreak of a viral [[bioweapon]] known as the [[T-Virus]], manufactured by [[Umbrella Corporation]].<ref name=\"characters\">{{cite book|title=Resident Evil Archives|date=November 9, 2005|publisher=[[BradyGames Publishing]]|isbn=0-7440-0655-4|pages=117\u2013121}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Resident Evil Archives|date=November 9, 2005|publisher=[[BradyGames Publishing]]|isbn=0-7440-0655-4|page=253}}</ref> The game begins at a [[gas station]] outside of the city, where rookie police officer [[Leon S. Kennedy]] meets college student [[Claire Redfield]], who is looking for her brother [[Chris Redfield]].\n\nAfter being separated following a car accident, Leon and Claire agree to meet up at the city's police department. The building is infested by zombies, and other monsters, including the \"[[Tyrant (Resident Evil)|Tyrant]]\",{{efn|Officially known as T-00, but commonly referred to as \"Mr. X\".}} who is dispatched to hunt down and kill any survivors. The creatures and various obstacles prevent Leon and Claire from actually reuniting as they are forced to find a way to escape the city.\n\n=== Claire scenario ===\nClaire encounters a young girl, Sherry Birkin, who is being pursued by a monstrous creature. The two manage to escape into the police station parking garage, where corrupt Police Chief Brian Irons abducts Sherry, and locks her in an abandoned orphanage. Claire soon receives a call from Irons to trade Sherry for a pendant she had dropped during the abduction, threatening to kill the little girl if Claire does not comply. Reluctantly, Claire agrees to do so.\n\nSherry tries to escape on her own, but is soon cornered by Irons. Before Irons can harm her, the creature that had been chasing Sherry returns and implants Irons with a parasite. Claire arrives to save Sherry, and the parasite bursts out of Irons' chest, killing him. As Claire and Sherry attempt to leave, the Tyrant arrives and chases the pair into an elevator, but is killed by the creature stalking Sherry. The creature then tries to attack Claire and Sherry, but accidentally causes the elevator to fall into the sewers. The resulting impact knocks Claire unconscious, and Sherry is forced to abandon her to escape.\n\nClaire is found by Annette, Sherry's mother. Annette reveals that the creature after Sherry is William, her husband. The Birkins developed the G-Virus for Umbrella; however, William planned to sell it to the U.S. military. Umbrella sent its paramilitary force to confiscate his work, leading to William being fatally shot. To avoid death and vowing revenge, William had injected himself with the G-Virus. The infected William hunted down the Umbrella soldiers in the sewers. During the carnage he shattered vials of the T-virus the troops had taken, infecting sewer rats and indirectly causing the Raccoon City outbreak. Now a mindless mutating beast, the G-Virus drives William to infect Sherry, as she is the closest genetic match to William and thus the most suitable host to spread the infection.\n\nClaire finds Sherry trapped in a trash compactor by Annette. Upon reaching her, however, Sherry falls ill. Annette realizes William has already infected Sherry and has Claire bring her to an Umbrella lab called NEST, where a vaccine is stored. Once there, Claire uses Sherry's pendant to unlock the vaccine, but William attacks. Claire sends Annette to administer the vaccine while she fights William. After seemingly killing him, Claire reunites with Annette, who has managed to cure Sherry before dying from internal injuries. Sherry tearfully bids her mother goodbye. As the facility enacts a self-destruct protocol, Claire and Sherry make their way to an evacuation train. William returns yet again, and Claire defeats him just as the train prepares to leave. Upon boarding, Claire discovers Leon there as well.\n\n=== Leon scenario ===\nLeon is saved from an infected dog by FBI agent, [[Ada Wong]]. They find reporter Ben Bertolucci in the holding cells; imprisoned by Irons for investigating Umbrella. As Ben tries to convince Leon to release him, the Tyrant kills Ben. While attempting to escape the police station, Leon is intercepted by the Tyrant but is again saved by Ada. Leon pledges to help Ada retrieve a G-Virus sample to prove Umbrella's corruption.\n\nIn the sewers, Annette Birkin ambushes the pair and shoots at Ada; Leon takes the bullet and passes out. Ada pursues Annette but is knocked into a trash compactor. Leon rescues her, and they descend to NEST via cable car, where Ada kisses Leon.\n\nAda, injured, requests that Leon obtain the G sample. In Birkin's lab, Leon obtains a sample but is attacked by William. Annette tries to kill him, but is mortally wounded. Leon defeats William and tends to Annette, who claims that Ada is a mercenary and will sell the virus to the highest bidder.\n\nLeon confronts Ada as the lab's self-destruct protocol begins, where she admits to being a mercenary. Ada demands the G-Virus sample from Leon at gunpoint, but Annette shoots Ada before succumbing to her injuries. As Ada falls off the bridge; Leon catches her, letting the virus sample fall into the abyss. Leon loses his grip and Ada falls.\n\nAs Leon attempts to escape the lab, he is ambushed by the Tyrant, now transformed into the larger and more powerful Super Tyrant and engages it in a final battle. Ada, having survived the fall, tosses a rocket launcher to him, which Leon uses to finally destroy the Super Tyrant. Leon boards the evacuation train, discovering Claire and Sherry already aboard.\n\n=== Ending ===\nAfter Leon, Claire, and Sherry reunite, William attacks the train, having mutated into a gigantic putrid mass of fangs and flesh. Claire and Leon are almost killed in the fight, but manage to uncouple the carriage occupied by William. The carriage falls behind and is consumed by the exploding lab, destroying William once and for all. As the three survivors finally escape Raccoon City, they vow to continue the fight against Umbrella.\n\n== Development ==\n[[File:Resident Evil 2 police car at E3 2018.jpg|thumb|Promotional booth at [[E3 2018]]]]\nThe original ''[[Resident Evil 2]]'' was released for the PlayStation in 1998. Following the release of the [[Resident Evil (2002 video game)|2002 remake of the first ''Resident Evil'']] for the [[GameCube]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/ir/english/interview/2008/vol01/index.html|title=Developer Interview 2008: vol01.Jun Takeuchi|date=September 30, 2008|publisher=[[Capcom Co., Ltd]]|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wKKUD5nb?url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/ir/english/interview/2008/vol01/index.html|archivedate=February 7, 2011|url-status=dead|accessdate=February 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/resident-evil-5_0_7?page=2|title=Resident Evil 5 Xbox 360 Hands On|author=Reed, Kristan|date=November 13, 2008|work=[[Eurogamer.net]]|publisher=Eurogamer Network Ltd|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5wGky94At?url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/resident-evil-5_0_7?page=2|archivedate=February 5, 2011|url-status=live|accessdate=February 5, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gametrailers.com/video/jun-takeuchi-resident-evil/46044|title=Jun Takeuchi Interview II|date=February 27, 2009|work=[[GameTrailers]]|publisher=[[MTV Networks]]|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6HcUlTCqy?url=http://www.gametrailers.com/videos/v7g5vi/resident-evil-5-jun-takeuchi-interview-ii|archivedate=June 24, 2013|url-status=live|accessdate=February 5, 2011}}</ref> Capcom considered a similar remake of ''Resident Evil 2'', but series creator [[Shinji Mikami]] did not want to divert development away from ''[[Resident Evil 4]]''.<ref>{{cite journal |script-title=ja:\u4e09\u4e26\u9054\u4e5f\u00d7\u4e09\u4e0a\u771f\u53f8 \u72ec\u5360\u5bfe\u8ac7 |journal=\u30cf\u30a4\u30d1\u30fc\u30ab\u30d7\u30b3\u30f3\u30b9\u30da\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb |date=June 11, 2002 |publisher=Sony Magazines Inc. |language=Japanese}}</ref> In August 2015, producer Yoshiaki Hirabayashi announced in a video that the remake had been approved and was in active development, ending the video with the phrase \"We Do It\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Senior|first1=Tom|title=Resident Evil 2 Remake is in development|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/resident-evil-2-remake-is-in-development/|website=PC Gamer|accessdate=January 25, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180125134449/http://www.pcgamer.com/resident-evil-2-remake-is-in-development/|archivedate=January 25, 2018}}</ref> No further details were released until Sony's [[E3 2018]] press conference, when Capcom released the debut trailer and gameplay footage and removed \"Remake\" from the title.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McWhertor |first1=Michael |title=Resident Evil 2 remake revealed, coming January 2019 |url=https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/11/17443046/resident-evil-2-remake-trailer-release-date-e3-2018 |website=Polygon |accessdate=June 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143127/https://www.polygon.com/e3/2018/6/11/17443046/resident-evil-2-remake-trailer-release-date-e3-2018 |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Romano |first1=Sal |title=Resident Evil 2 announced for PS4, Xbox One, and PC |url=https://gematsu.com/2018/06/resident-evil-2-announced-ps4-xbox-one-pc |website=Gematsu |accessdate=June 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612024124/https://gematsu.com/2018/06/resident-evil-2-announced-ps4-xbox-one-pc |archive-date=June 12, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Hideki Kamiya]], director of the original ''Resident Evil 2'', said that he had pushed Capcom to create a remake for years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McWhertor |first1=Michael |title=Original Resident Evil 2 director says he pestered Capcom for a remake |url=https://www.polygon.com/2016/6/20/11982568/resident-evil-2-remake-director-hideki-kamiya-capcom |website=Polygon |accessdate=September 4, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904084535/https://www.polygon.com/2016/6/20/11982568/resident-evil-2-remake-director-hideki-kamiya-capcom |archive-date=September 4, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Hirabayashi said the team was striving to capture the spirit of the original game, and that the team incorporated feedback received about ''[[Resident Evil 6]]'', a game he also produced.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.videogamer.com/news/resident-evil-2-remake-progressing-resi-6-feedback-being-taken-on-board-says-producer|title=Resident Evil 2 Remake 'progressing'; Resi 6 feedback being 'taken on board', says producer - VideoGamer.com|access-date=September 3, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181123130416/https://www.videogamer.com/news/resident-evil-2-remake-progressing-resi-6-feedback-being-taken-on-board-says-producer|archive-date=November 23, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nTo meet modern expectations, the team decided to alter some character designs to better match the more photorealistic setting; for example, Leon no longer wears large shoulder pads, which were added to distinguish his original, low-polygon model. Ada Wong's red dress was dropped in favor of a trenchcoat with sunglasses for similar reasons. Though they strove to make a \"modern, accessible\" game, they focused on horror over action, hoping to preserve a [[claustrophobia|claustrophobic]] feel.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.polygon.com/interviews/2018/10/8/17911258/resident-evil-2-remakes-changes-additions-new-interview|title=How Capcom updated Resident Evil 2 for 2019|work=Polygon|accessdate=October 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181120192112/https://www.polygon.com/interviews/2018/10/8/17911258/resident-evil-2-remakes-changes-additions-new-interview|archive-date=November 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The game uses the RE Engine, the same [[game engine]] used for ''[[Resident Evil 7: Biohazard]]'', which allowed for Capcom to modernize the gameplay.<ref name=\"e32018announce\"/> Producer Tsuyoshi Kanda acknowledged the difficulty of making zombies seem scary and threatening, as they had become ubiquitous in entertainment media since the release of the original ''[[Resident Evil (1996 video game)|Resident Evil]]'' in 1996.<ref name=\":0\" /> By removing the fixed camera angles, the team had to use different ways to conceal enemies, using elements such as room layout, lighting, and smoke.<ref name=\":0\" /> The new camera system also affected the sound design, as it no longer made sense for sound to come from a fixed source.<ref name=\":0\" /> The faces of several character models are based on scans of real people. Leon S. Kennedy is based on model Eduard Badaluta, Claire Redfield is based on model Jordan McEwen, and Marvin Branagh is based on music producer Patrick Levar.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ashcraft |first1=Brian |title=The Faces Behind Resident Evil 2's Remake Characters |url=https://kotaku.com/the-faces-behind-resident-evil-2s-remake-characters-1827440505 |accessdate=January 21, 2019 |work=[[Kotaku]] |date=July 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123000716/https://kotaku.com/the-faces-behind-resident-evil-2s-remake-characters-1827440505 |archive-date=January 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe game features a [[Dolby Atmos]] soundtrack.<ref>https://news.xbox.com/en-us/2017/11/13/xbox-one-x-windows-sonic-dolby-atmos-feature/</ref>\n\n''Resident Evil 2'' was released on [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]] and [[Windows]] worldwide on January 25, 2019.<ref name=\"e32018announce\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/06/12/e3-2018-resident-evil-2-remake-release-date-announced|title=E3 2018: Resident Evil 2 Remake Release Date Announced|last=Osborn|first=Alex|date=June 11, 2018|website=IGN|language=en-US|accessdate=June 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612152506/http://www.ign.com/articles/2018/06/12/e3-2018-resident-evil-2-remake-release-date-announced|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The game supports enhancements on the [[PlayStation 4 Pro]] and [[Xbox One X]], offering either [[4K resolution]] or 60 [[frames per second]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cryer |first1=Hirun |last2=Orry |first2=Tom |title=Resident Evil 2 Remake Release Date, Gameplay Footage, 4K/60FPS, PC System Specs - Everything we Know |url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/13-07-2018-resident-evil-2-remake-release-date |website=USGamer |accessdate=July 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180713205152/https://www.usgamer.net/articles/13-07-2018-resident-evil-2-remake-release-date |archive-date=July 13, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> A [[game demo|demo]] known as the ''1-Shot Demo'' was released on January 11, 2019. It ends after 30 minutes and does not allow repeat playthroughs, however the same demo would later be rereleased as the \"R.P.D. Demo\" and does allow repeat playthroughs.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Watts |first1=Steve |title=Resident Evil 2 1-Shot Demo Out Now For Some |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/resident-evil-2-1-shot-demo-out-now-for-some/1100-6464323/ |website=GameSpot |accessdate=January 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Jeffrey |first1=Cal |title=How to play the Resident Evil 2 One-Shot demo more than once |url=https://www.techspot.com/news/78286-how-play-resident-evil-2-one-shot-demo.html |website=Techspot |accessdate=January 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190116030321/https://www.techspot.com/news/78286-how-play-resident-evil-2-one-shot-demo.html |archive-date=January 16, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> A [[downloadable content]] game mode, known as ''Ghost Survivors'', was released on February 15, 2019.<ref name=\"SC\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.siliconera.com/2019/02/13/resident-evil-2-the-ghost-survivors-dlc-will-behave-like-the-4th-survivor-and-the-tofu-survivor/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=February 14, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190214174513/https://www.siliconera.com/2019/02/13/resident-evil-2-the-ghost-survivors-dlc-will-behave-like-the-4th-survivor-and-the-tofu-survivor/ |archive-date=February 14, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.gamerevolution.com/guides/497475-resident-evil-2-the-ghost-survivors-4th-scenario-no-way-out-unlock-secret |title=Archived copy |access-date=February 27, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227182037/https://www.gamerevolution.com/guides/497475-resident-evil-2-the-ghost-survivors-4th-scenario-no-way-out-unlock-secret |archive-date=February 27, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n{{Clr}}\n\n==Reception==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = (PC) 89/100<ref name=\"MCPC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/resident-evil-2 |title=Resident Evil 2 for PC Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531155715/https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/resident-evil-2 |archive-date=May 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><br />(PS4) 91/100<ref name=\"MCPS4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/resident-evil-2 |title=Resident Evil 2 for PlayStation 4 Reviews |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531155848/https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/resident-evil-2 |archive-date=May 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><br />(XONE) 93/100<ref name=\"MCXONE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/resident-evil-2|title=Resident Evil 2 for Xbox One Reviews|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531155947/https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/resident-evil-2|archive-date=May 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Destruct = 9/10<ref name=\"Destruct\">{{cite web |last=Carter |first=Chris |date=January 22, 2019 |url=https://www.destructoid.com/review-resident-evil-2-2019--538881.phtml |title=Review: Resident Evil 2 (2019) |website=[[Destructoid]] |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124044407/https://www.destructoid.com/review-resident-evil-2-2019--538881.phtml |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| EGM = 9.5/10<ref>{{cite web |last1=Patterson |first1=Mollie L. |title=Resident Evil 2 review |url=http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/resident-evil-2-review/ |website=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]] |date=January 22, 2019 |accessdate=January 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130221952/http://www.egmnow.com/articles/reviews/resident-evil-2-review/ |archive-date=January 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| Fam = 37/40<ref>{{cite web |title=Famitsu review scores (1/15/19) |url=https://nintendoeverything.com/famitsu-review-scores-1-15-19/ |website=Nintendo Everything |date=January 15, 2019 |accessdate=January 21, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124044313/https://nintendoeverything.com/famitsu-review-scores-1-15-19/ |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| GI = 9.5/10<ref name=\"GI\">{{cite web |last=Reeves |first=Ben |date=January 22, 2019 |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/Resident%20Evil%202%20game%20informer%20Review |title=Resident Evil 2 Review |website=[[Game Informer]] |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124045039/https://www.gameinformer.com/Resident%20Evil%202%20game%20informer%20Review |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| GameRev = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Resident Evil 2 remake review {{!}} The perfect Resi game? |url=https://www.gamerevolution.com/review/485467-resident-evil-2-remake-review-ps4-xbox-one-pc |website=[[Game Revolution]] |date=January 22, 2019 |accessdate=January 29, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130220854/https://www.gamerevolution.com/review/485467-resident-evil-2-remake-review-ps4-xbox-one-pc |archive-date=January 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| GSpot = 9/10<ref name=\"GSpot\">{{cite web |last=Fillari |first=Alessandro |date=January 22, 2019 |title=Resident Evil 2 Review - Raccoon City Revisited |url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/resident-evil-2-review-raccoon-city-revisited/1900-6417071/ |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124044753/https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/resident-evil-2-review-revisiting-raccoon-city/1900-6417071/ |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| IGN = 9.0/10<ref>{{cite web |last=Hatfield |first=Daemon |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |title=Resident Evil 2 Review |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/01/22/resident-evil-2-review |website=[[IGN]] |date=January 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124045232/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/01/22/resident-evil-2-review |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| USG = 4.5/5<ref name=\"USGamer\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/resident-evil-2-review|title=Resident Evil 2 Review|last=Kim|first=Matt|date=January 22, 2019|website=USgamer|language=en|access-date=January 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123225054/https://www.usgamer.net/articles/resident-evil-2-review|archive-date=January 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n\nFollowing its E3 2018 showing, ''Resident Evil 2'' won the \"Best of Show\" award at the 2018 [[Game Critics Awards]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fogel |first1=Stefanie |title=Game Critics Awards 2018 Names \u2018Resident Evil 2\u2019 Remake Best of Show |url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/game-critics-awards-2018-winners-1202863599/ |website=Variety |accessdate=July 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816173408/https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/game-critics-awards-2018-winners-1202863599/ |archive-date=August 16, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The ''1-Shot Demo'' received over 4.7{{nbsp}}million downloads worldwide.<ref name=\"capcom-sales\">{{cite news |title=Resident Evil 2 Ships 3 Million Units Worldwide in First Week of Sales! |url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/ir/english/news/html/e190129.html |accessdate=January 29, 2019 |publisher=[[Capcom]] |date=January 29, 2019 |language=ja |archive-url=https://archive.today/20190208132922/http://www.capcom.co.jp/ir/english/news/html/e190129.html |archive-date=February 8, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''Resident Evil 2'' received \"universal acclaim\" for the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One versions, and \"generally favorable reviews\" for the PC according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MCPC\"/><ref name=\"MCPS4\"/><ref name=\"MCXONE\"/>\n\n''[[Game Informer]]'' said that \"''Resident Evil 2'' not only looks great, it plays well, and it forces you into a series of dark encounters that are a total rush.\"<ref name=\"GI\"/> ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote that it was \"a reminder of how beautifully crafted survival horror games were in their heyday.\"<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web |last=Stuart |first=Keith |date=January 22, 2019 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/games/2019/jan/22/resident-evil-2-review-genre-defining-horror-loaded-with-dread |title=Resident Evil 2 review \u2013 genre-defining horror, loaded with dread |website=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124045704/https://www.theguardian.com/games/2019/jan/22/resident-evil-2-review-genre-defining-horror-loaded-with-dread |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' described it as a \"thrilling return to the legacy of the 1998 original\".<ref name=\"telegraph\">{{cite web |last=Hoggins |first=Tom |date=January 22, 2019 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/reviews/resident-evil-2-remake-review-survival-horror-perfection/ |title=Resident Evil 2 remake review: Survival horror perfection |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=January 22, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124045536/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gaming/reviews/resident-evil-2-remake-review-survival-horror-perfection/ |archive-date=January 24, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''[[IGN]]'' originally gave the game an 8.8 in their review, only to increase it to a 9.0 after being made aware of the unlockable second playthrough that presents the story from another point of view. They stated in their review that \"Capcom did a fantastic job of resurrecting all the best parts of the classic ''Resident Evil 2'' and making it look, sound, and play like a 2019 game.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/01/22/resident-evil-2-review|title=Resident Evil 2 review|website=[[IGN]]|first=Daemon|last=Hatfield|date=January 22, 2019|accessdate=January 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190124045232/https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/01/22/resident-evil-2-review|archive-date=January 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''[[Destructoid]]'' called it \"A hallmark of excellence. There may be flaws, but they are negligible and won't cause massive damage.\"<ref name=\"Destruct\"/> ''[[Eurogamer]]'' described it as \"a masterly reimagining of a modern classic\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-01-22-resident-evil-2-review|title=Resident Evil 2 review - a masterly reimagining of a modern classic|website=[[Eurogamer]]|first=Aoife|last=Wilson|date=January 22, 2019|accessdate=January 22, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123042417/https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2019-01-22-resident-evil-2-review|archive-date=January 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' said ''Resident Evil 2'' showcases \"the very best of survival horror\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/1/22/18192509/resident-evil-2-remake-review|title=Resident Evil 2 is everything a video game remake should be|last=McWhertor|first=Michael|date=January 22, 2019|website=Polygon|access-date=January 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123223614/https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/1/22/18192509/resident-evil-2-remake-review|archive-date=January 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> while ''[[Kotaku]]'' also gave it similar praise, saying it \"provides some of the best moments in the franchise\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/resident-evil-2-the-kotaku-review-1831951036|title=Resident Evil 2: The Kotaku Review|last=Alexandra|first=Heather|website=Kotaku|language=en-US|access-date=January 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123005247/https://kotaku.com/resident-evil-2-the-kotaku-review-1831951036|archive-date=January 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[GameSpot]]'' said that with ''Resident Evil 2'', \"the classic survival horror franchise embraces its past in a new, exciting way\".<ref name=\"GSpot\"/>\n\n===Sales===\nThe game shipped three{{nbsp}}million copies worldwide in its first week of sales, rising to four million within a month with over one million on PC.<ref name=\"capcom-sales\"/><ref>{{cite web |last=Romano |first=Sal |title=Resident Evil 2 first week shipments top three million |url=https://gematsu.com/2019/01/resident-evil-2-first-week-shipments-top-three-million |website=Gematsu |date=January 29, 2019 |accessdate=January 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129181446/https://gematsu.com/2019/01/resident-evil-2-first-week-shipments-top-three-million |archive-date=January 29, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Makuch |first=Eddie |title=Resident Evil 2 Remake Sales Hit A New Milestone |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/resident-evil-2-remake-sales-hit-a-new-milestone/1100-6465220/ |website=[[GameSpot]] |date=March 1, 2019 |accessdate=November 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191210155110/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/resident-evil-2-remake-sales-hit-a-new-milestone/1100-6465220/ |archive-date=December 10, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Moyse |first=Chris |title=Resident Evil 2 pops one million sales on PC |url=https://www.destructoid.com/resident-evil-2-pops-one-million-sales-on-pc-546769.phtml |website=[[Destructoid]] |date=March 18, 2019 |accessdate=March 18, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330063833/https://www.destructoid.com/resident-evil-2-pops-one-million-sales-on-pc-546769.phtml |archive-date=March 30, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> It became Capcom's second biggest launch on [[Steam (software)|Steam]] after ''[[Monster Hunter: World]]'' from 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last=Jones |first=Ali |title=Resident Evil 2 is Capcom\u2019s second-best Steam launch ever |url=https://www.pcgamesn.com/resident-evil-2/resident-evil-2-sales |website=[[PCGamesN]] |date=January 25, 2019 |accessdate=January 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190126045755/https://www.pcgamesn.com/resident-evil-2/resident-evil-2-sales |archive-date=January 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''Resident Evil 2'' debuted at number two on the Japanese charts with 252,848 retail sales, after ''[[Kingdom Hearts III]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Romano |first=Sal |title=Media Create Sales: 1/21/19 \u2013 1/27/19 |url=https://gematsu.com/2019/01/media-create-sales-1-21-19-1-27-19|website=Gematsu |date=January 30, 2019 |accessdate=January 30, 2019  |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190130153116/https://gematsu.com/2019/01/media-create-sales-1-21-19-1-27-19 |archive-date=January 30, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u300cKINGDOM HEARTS III\u300d61\u4e07\u672c\uff0c\u300c\u30d0\u30a4\u30aa\u30cf\u30b6\u30fc\u30c9 RE:2\u300d25\u4e072000\u672c\u306e\u300c\u9031\u9593\u8ca9\u58f2\u30e9\u30f3\u30ad\u30f3\u30b0\uff0b\u300d |url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/117/G011794/20190130079/ |work=[[4Gamer.net]] |date=January 30, 2019 |accessdate=January 30, 2019 |language=Japanese|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190201131445/https://www.4gamer.net/games/117/G011794/20190130079/ |archive-date=February 1, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> As of March, the game was still among the top 20 best selling video games in Japan with more than 352,000 sold copies.<ref>{{cite web |last=Romano |first=Sal |title=Media Create Sales: 3/4/19 \u2013 3/10/19 |url=https://gematsu.com/2019/03/media-create-sales-3-4-19-3-10-19 |website=Gematsu |date=March 13, 2019 |accessdate=March 28, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190313185936/https://gematsu.com/2019/03/media-create-sales-3-4-19-3-10-19 |archive-date=March 13, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> ''Resident Evil 2'' also topped the UK charts, becoming Capcom's biggest UK launch since ''[[Resident Evil 7: Biohazard]]'' (2017) in physical retail sale, and was the UK's best-selling game in January 2019, despite being available for only two days.<ref>{{cite web |last=Khan |first=Zarmena |title=Resident Evil 2 Was UK Retail\u2019s Best-Selling Game in January 2019 Despite Being on Shelves for 2 Days |url=https://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2019/02/02/resident-evil-2-sales-jan-2019-uk-retail/ |website=[[PlayStation LifeStyle]] |date=February 2, 2019 |accessdate=February 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190203052904/https://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2019/02/02/resident-evil-2-sales-jan-2019-uk-retail/ |archive-date=February 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> By December 2019, the game had sold over 5.8 million copies, which was more than the original game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kerr |first1=Chris |title=Resident Evil 2 remake has passed 5 million sales |url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/355522/Resident_Evil_2_remake_has_passed_5_million_sales.php |website=Gamasutra |accessdate=11 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191211214652/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/355522/Resident_Evil_2_remake_has_passed_5_million_sales.php |archive-date=December 11, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Platinum Titles |url=http://www.capcom.co.jp/ir/english/finance/million.html |website=[[Capcom]] |accessdate=24 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Award !! Category !! Result !! Ref\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"3\" | 2018\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Game Critics Awards]]\n| Best of Show\n| {{Won}}\n| rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Watts |first=Steve |title=Resident Evil 2 Wins Top Honor In E3 Game Critics Awards |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/resident-evil-2-wins-top-honor-in-e3-game-critics-/1100-6460135/ |website=GameSpot |date=July 5, 2018 |accessdate=November 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180803224106/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/resident-evil-2-wins-top-honor-in-e3-game-critics-/1100-6460135/ |archive-date=August 3, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| Best Console Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Best Action/Adventure Game\n| {{Nom}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" rowspan=\"8\" | 2019\n| [[Japan Game Awards]]\n| Award for Excellence\n| {{Won}}\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | <ref>{{cite web |last=Craddock |first=Ryan |ti